name: Kartik Soni
review_text:
The Taj Mahal, located in Agra, is one of the most iconic and admired monuments in the world. Built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal, this majestic mausoleum is a symbol of eternal love and architectural brilliance. Completed in 1653, the Taj Mahal is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of the Seven Wonders of the World.

The structure's beauty lies in its perfect symmetry, intricate marble work, and stunning gardens. Made from white marble, the Taj Mahal reflects changing hues depending on the time of day and the light, making it a visual treat at sunrise, sunset, and even under moonlight. The central dome, flanked by four minarets, along with the detailed carvings and calligraphy, showcases the pinnacle of Mughal architecture, blending Persian, Islamic, and Indian styles.

The interior of the Taj Mahal is equally mesmerizing, with inlaid precious stones forming intricate floral patterns. At the heart of the mausoleum lie the cenotaphs of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan, a quiet reminder of the love that inspired the creation of this masterpiece.

Visitors from around the world flock to the Taj Mahal, not only for its historical significance but also for its serene beauty. The well-maintained gardens, with the reflection of the monument in the central pool, offer a peaceful ambiance for tourists to take in the grandeur of this timeless monument. Visiting the Taj Mahal is truly a once-in-a-lifetime experience.

name: Anand Singh
review_text:
I had the privilege of visiting the Taj Mahal, and it was a truly breathtaking experience. The sheer scale and beauty of this stunning monument took my breath away. The intricate marble work, the perfectly proportioned architecture, and the serene gardens all combined to create an unforgettable atmosphere.

As I walked through the complex, I was struck by the history and romance that surrounds this iconic wonder. The story of Shah Jahans love for his wife, Mumtaz Mahal, and the tragic circumstances that led to the Tajs construction, added a poignant depth to my visit.

The attention to detail in every aspect of the Tajs design is awe-inspiring. From the delicate calligraphy to the intricate inlays, every element seems to have been carefully considered to create a masterpiece. And yet, despite the opulence, the Taj exudes a sense of elegance and restraint.

As the sun began to set, the Taj transformed before my eyes, its white marble glowing with a soft golden light. It was as if the monument was radiating an otherworldly beauty, leaving me speechless and humbled.

The Taj Mahal is a must-visit for anyone seeking to experience the beauty and wonder of human creation. It is a testament to the power of love, art, and architecture to transcend time and touch our souls.

name: Dr Amit Agarwal
review_text:
The Taj Mahal, located in Agra, India, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of the most iconic monuments in the world. Built by the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan between 1631 and 1648, it was constructed in memory of his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal, who died during childbirth. The Taj Mahal is a stunning example of Mughal architecture, blending elements of Islamic, Persian, and Indian styles.

The white marble mausoleum is known for its intricate inlay work of precious stones, symmetrical gardens, and reflecting pool, which enhances its beauty. The main dome, flanked by four minarets, is the most recognizable feature, symbolizing eternal love and devotion. The interior houses the cenotaphs of both Shah Jahan and Mumtaz Mahal, though their actual graves lie beneath the structure.

Over the centuries, the Taj Mahal has become a symbol of India's rich cultural heritage and a major tourist attraction, drawing millions of visitors annually. Its ethereal beauty, especially at sunrise and sunset, captivates onlookers. Despite environmental concerns and the need for preservation, the Taj Mahal remains a timeless masterpiece and a testament to the enduring power of love.

name: Tonje Aasen
review_text:
Lovely place, nothing to say about the view and the sights. Recommend being there relatively early in the day. Remember that it can get very hot on certain days, so remember to both eat and drink before going inside. When you get there, you buy a ticket, which can also be done online. There you can pay for a shuttle, type of large tuktuk for a few rupees, as it takes 5ish minutes to walk to the entrance from the car park. You will be given a bottle of water and socks for your shoes. You must use the socks to see inside the temple. If you have lost or forgotten them, you can also take off your shoes and put on your socks. It is not allowed to take pictures inside the temple, but everywhere else.

You will get offers from many for guided tours for from 500 to 2000 rupees, choose for yourself and carefully. You also get offers from photographers, I dont know if they are professional, and it costs from 1000 rupees.

There are also a good number of small shops on the outside, the prices are reasonable for the most part. Recommend shopping after youve been inside, as you cant take things with you into the Taj Mahal.

Also note that you cannot bring a computer, smoke, lighter, chewing gum, drops, food, drink or anything similar with you. You must either give this up or attach it to the guard. Recommends leaving everything, except the most necessary, in the car.

I also have to say a little about the toilets there. They are unmanned and dont seem like anyone is cleaning anything. There is a toilet there, both a toilet and a floor toilet. They looked absolutely terrible. People had peed and sprayed water all over the toilet, not a hygienic place. Preferably go to the bathroom before or after, as these barely work in an emergency. And, of course, no toilet paper for those who need it.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
10-30 min

Reservation recommended
Not sure
review_translated_text:
Nydelig plass, ingen ting a si pa utsikten og serverdigheten. Anbefaler a vaere der relativt tidlig pa dagen. Husk at det kan bli veldig varmt visse dager, sa husk a bade spise og drikke for man gar inn. Nar man kommer dit sa kjoper man billett, kan ogsa gjores online. Der kan man betale for en shuttle, type stor tuktuk for noen rupi, da det tar 5 ish minutter a ga til inngangen fra parkeringsplassen. Du far utlevert en flaske med vann og sokker til skoene dine. Sokkene ma du bruke for a se inne i tempelet. Har du mistet eller glemt dem, sa kan du ogsa ta av deg sko og ga pa sokkene. Det er ikke lov a ta bilde inne i tempelet, men over alt pa resten.


Du far tilbud fra mangen om guidet tur for fra 500 til 2000 rupi, velg selv og med omhu. Man far ogsa tilbud fra fotograf, om de er profesjonelle vet jeg ikke, og det koster fra 1000 rupi.


Der er ogsa en god del sma butikker pa utsiden, prisene er fornuftige pa det meste. Anbefaler a handle etter du har vaert inne, da du ikke far ting med deg inn i Taj Mahal.


Vaer ogsa obs pa at du ikke kan ha med deg verken pc, royk, lighter, tyggegummi, drops, mat, drikke eller noe lignende. Dette ma du enten gi fra deg eller legge ved vakten. Anbefaler a la alt, utenom det mest nodvendige, bli i bilen.


Jeg ma ogsa si litt om toalettene der. De er ubemannet og virker ikke som noen rengjor noe som helst. Det er toalett der, bade klosett og gulv toalett. De sag absolutt heilt forferdelige ut. Folk hadde tisset og sprayet vann over hele toalettet, ikkje hygieniskt en plass. Gjerne ga pa do for eller etter, da disse sa vidt funker i noden. Og, saklart, ingen toalettpapir for dem som trenger det.

name: Asrph Khan
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is truly a wonder of the world! Words cannot do justice to its beauty and magnificence. The white marble structure is stunning, especially during sunrise and sunset when it takes on a warm glow. The intricate carvings, the symmetry, and the story behind its creation make it a must-visit. The gardens are beautifully maintained, adding to the serene atmosphere. Its a place that combines history, architecture, and romance in a way that leaves you in awe. Highly recommend visiting with a guide to fully appreciate the history and details. A visit to Agra isn't complete without experiencing the Taj Mahal.

name: Kumari Kavya
review_text:
As a visitor to the Taj Mahal, I can honestly say that its one of the most breathtaking sights Ive ever seen. The intricate carvings, the pristine white marble, and the sheer scale of the monument are simply awe-inspiring.
Its easy to see why the Taj Mahal is considered a symbol of love and devotion. The story behind its construction is incredibly touching.
While the crowds can be a bit overwhelming at times, its definitely worth dealing with to experience such a magnificent piece of architecture. I recommend visiting early in the morning or late in the afternoon to avoid the biggest crowds.
Overall, the Taj Mahal is a must-see destination for anyone visiting India. Its a truly unforgettable experience that will stay with you for a lifetime.

name: Gopal Kumar
review_text:
Taj Mahal is a famous mausoleum located in Agra, India. It was built by Mughal emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal. The Taj Mahal is constructed from white marble, and its architecture is unique. Its main dome is 35 meters high, and there are four minarets surrounding it. The gardens and water bodies of Taj Mahal make it even more beautiful. It was declared as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983 and is considered a symbol of love.

name: SANKET HANKARE
review_text:
1. Its very beautiful. Advisable to get tickets online or from the QR scanner for payment available approximately 100m before the turnstile entry gate.

2. Best time is to visit early in the morning. Reach here at 6am and you will find less crowd and low temperature. There are few small shops inside providing water bottles and snacks.

3. For Indian tourists, seeing Taj Mahal from outside costs 50 INR and to get inside it costs 200 INR extra. So in total its 250/-. However there is a small discount for online tickets. You can get the above tickets in two parts of 50 and 200 from the counter or also directly 250. So if one takes only INR 50 ticket to just watch the Taj Mahal but later wishes to also get inside it, he can take 200/- ticket from the counter just outside the main Taj Mahal monument.

4. Inside the Taj Mahal you can go barefoot or with shoe cover. The reusable cloth shoe cover is available free of cost at the counter which is just outside the main Taj Mahal monument entrance. The shoe cover then needs to be deposited in the big containers at the exit.

5. Overall it will take 2-4 hours to complete the tour. The entry starts at approximately 5:30am in the morning till approximately 5 or 5:30 pm in the evening. However the selling of tickets both online and offline may stop early at around 5pm approximately. So at least by 4:30 pm one should reach the place.

6. The outermost entry gate is just at one minute walking distance from the Taj Mahal Metro Station. From this outermost entry gate, it will take 10-45min to reach the actual Taj Mahal by walking. All depending on the crowd and timing of the visit. It took us around 30 min overall including the time spent in the entry line, and also it was our first visit so that also adds to the time. Also we went on Saturday.

7. There are some 11-seater (approx) golf carts that are available just inside the outermost entrance gate for those who dont want to walk. They help you save only five to ten minutes of walking time. So we didnt opt for it.

8. Best time to reach is before 7am or after 4pm.

9. Its closed on Friday.

10. Taking photos is allowed almost everywhere with few exceptions.

11. Food items are not allowed to be carried inside. Water bottles are allowed. Checking of bags is properly done at the turnstile entry gate. However it may be possible to sneak in a toffee or two.

name: Madhusudhan Katariya
review_text:
the Taj is a white marble mausoleum located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India,Taj Mahal was built in the memory of Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan (from reign 1628 to 1658) in the memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal, the construction work of the Taj Mahal began in 1632. Shah Jahan wanted the world to remember Mumtaz and his love story, that is why he wanted to make some historical heritage in his memory. but still to enhance its beauty and work up to 10 years.
The construction of the Taj Mahal was completed in about 1653 and at that time the cost was approximately 32 million rupees, the construction of the Taj Mahal was done by 25,000+ craftsmen. Ustad Ahmad Lahauri is often regarded as its chief architect.

The Taj is a white marble mausoleum located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India. The Taj Mahal was built by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan (reigned 1628 to 1658) in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal. Construction of the Taj Mahal began in 1632. Shahjahan wanted the world to remember Mumtaz and her love story, that is why he wanted to create some historical heritage in her memory. In which Taj Mahal was built. The construction of Taj Mahal was completed around 1643 but still it took up to 10 years to enhance its beauty and work. The construction of Taj Mahal was completed around 1653 and its cost at that time was around Rs 32 crores, Taj Mahal was constructed by more than 25,000 artisans. Ustad Ahmed Lahauri is often considered its chief architect.

name: dinesh Jangra
review_text: The Taj Mahal is an extraordinary monument that symbolizes love and architectural brilliance. Nestled in Agra, India, it was commissioned by Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal.This breathtaking structure is crafted from white marble, which gleams under the sun and changes hues with the time of day. The intricate inlay work and delicate carvings showcase the artistry of Mughal architecture.Visitors are often awed by the symmetry and grandeur of the gardens leading to the mausoleum. As you walk through the serene pathways, the ethereal beauty of the Taj captures your heart.The experience is not just visual; its an emotional journey that speaks of eternal love.Overall, the Taj Mahal is a must-visit for anyone exploring India, offering a perfect blend of history, beauty, and romance that leaves a lasting impression.

name: Himanshu Singh
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is truly a marvel of architecture and a symbol of love that should be on everyones bucket list. As you approach the monument, its stunning white marble facade shines brilliantly against the blue sky, creating a breathtaking sight. The intricate carvings and inlaid gemstones tell a story of exquisite craftsmanship that leaves you in awe.

Inside, the serene atmosphere and the beautiful central dome add to the monuments allure. The surrounding gardens provide a peaceful setting for reflection and photography, making it a perfect spot to appreciate the beauty of this UNESCO World Heritage Site.
Visiting at sunrise or sunset is particularly magical, as the changing light casts a warm glow on the marble. Its important to arrive early to avoid the crowds and fully enjoy the experience.

Overall, the Taj Mahal is not just a monument; its an unforgettable experience that captures the heart and imagination. A must-visit when in India!
Visited on
Weekend

The Taj Mahal is truly a magnificent sight, living up to its reputation as one of the wonders of the world. The intricate marble work, the symmetrical gardens, and the reflection in the pool are mesmerizing.

However, be prepared for high humidity, especially if you're visiting during the warmer months. It can get quite uncomfortable, so I recommend carrying water, wearing light clothing, and taking breaks in the shaded areas.

Despite the weather, the beauty of this iconic monument makes it worth the visit..

name: Mohammed Raees Babu Vk
review_text:
Taj Mahal - A Timeless Wonder

The Taj Mahal, an iconic symbol of love, is a must-visit marvel located in Agra, India. Built by Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal, this UNESCO World Heritage site is renowned for its stunning white marble architecture and intricate craftsmanship.

Visiting Hours:

* Open from 6:00 AM to 6:30 PM (except Fridays).
* Night viewing is available on full moon nights and two days before and after.

Ticket Prices (as of 2024):

* Indian visitors: 50
* Foreign tourists: 1100
* SAARC/BIMSTEC visitors: 540
* Children under 15: Free

Best Time to Visit:

* Early morning or during sunset for mesmerizing views. Winter months (October to March) offer pleasant weather.

Facilities:

* Wheelchair access is available.
* No food or large bags are allowed inside, but locker facilities are available.

name: Roopesh Krishnan
review_text:
The Taj Mahal in Agra is an iconic symbol of love and one of the most magnificent architectural marvels in the world. Built in the 17th century by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal, this UNESCO World Heritage site is often regarded as the epitome of Mughal architecture, blending Persian, Islamic, and Indian styles seamlessly.

The first sight of the Taj Mahal is breathtaking. Its pristine white marble facade glistens under the sun, reflecting in the pool that runs along the front gardens, creating a picture-perfect view.
The symmetry, intricate carvings, and inlay work of semi-precious stones make it a masterpiece of art and craftsmanship. The central dome, flanked by four smaller domes and four slender minarets, creates an awe-inspiring silhouette against the sky.
Inside the mausoleum, the artistry continues with delicate marble lattice screens and intricate pietra dura (stone inlay) work. The serene interior houses the cenotaphs of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan, surrounded by a peaceful ambiance that invites quiet reflection.
The surrounding gardens, known as the Charbagh, are beautifully landscaped and provide a serene setting to enjoy the beauty of the monument from different angles.

The Yamuna River flowing behind the Taj Mahal adds to its tranquility, especially at sunrise and sunset when the monument takes on different hues, from soft pink to golden and pearly white.The experience of visiting the Taj Mahal is further enriched by knowledgeable guides who provide insights into its history, architecture, and the poignant love story behind its creation. Despite the crowds, the monuments beauty and historical significance make it worth the visit.
Overall, the Taj Mahal is not just a monument but an experience that leaves visitors spellbound by its beauty, historical significance, and the timeless love story it represents. A visit to India would be incomplete without witnessing this wonder of the world.

For this you will have to pay 200 extra and children up to 15 years of age are free to take them anywhere in Taj Mahal. Means no ticket. If you want to go to Taj Mahal, you will get shoe covers for which you do not have to pay anything extra. If you do not want to go to the Taj Mahal and just want to roam around the Taj Mahal, then you do not have to cover your shoes.

name: sunil Jakhar
review_text:
My Review of the Taj Mahal

Visiting the Taj Mahal was an unforgettable experience. This iconic monument lives up to its reputation as one of the most beautiful and awe-inspiring places in the world. Here are my thoughts:

1. Architectural Beauty:
The Taj Mahal's architecture is simply breathtaking. The white marble seems to glow, especially at sunrise and sunset. The intricate carvings and the perfect symmetry make it feel like a work of art. The dome and the four surrounding minarets are an impressive sight up close.

2. Emotional Connection:
Knowing the history behind the Taj Mahal, built as a symbol of love by Emperor Shah Jahan for his wife, added a deeply emotional layer to my visit. It feels more than just a building--it's a tribute to eternal love and devotion, which made the experience even more meaningful.

3. Serene Surroundings:
The gardens and the reflection pool surrounding the monument create a peaceful atmosphere. Despite the crowds, I found moments of quiet where I could simply appreciate the beauty and calmness of the environment.

4. Crowds and Experience:
The Taj Mahal can get quite crowded, especially during peak times. However, even with the number of people, the beauty of the place shines through. I would recommend visiting early in the morning to avoid large crowds and enjoy a more peaceful experience.

5. Overall Impressions:
Whether you're interested in history, architecture, or simply want to witness one of the wonders of the world, the Taj Mahal is a must-see. It's a timeless monument that captivates you from the moment you step inside the gates. I left feeling inspired and moved by both its beauty and the story behind it.

name: Md. Johirul Islam
review_text:
The Taj Mahal, a symbol of eternal love, takes on a magical glow in the early morning hours that is truly indescribable. As the first rays of the sun gently kiss the pristine white marble, the entire monument seems to radiate with a soft, golden light. This moment, fleeting and delicate, gives the Taj an ethereal beauty, as if its floating in a dreamlike world. The cool morning air adds to the serenity, allowing visitors to absorb the grandeur of this architectural masterpiece in peace and reflection.

The symmetry of the Taj Mahal, with its majestic domes and minarets, stands in stark contrast to the quiet of the early hours. There's a stillness, broken only by the songs of birds and the soft murmur of the Yamuna River in the distance. The marble's intricate carvings and inlaid gemstones sparkle subtly, enhanced by the soft sunlight, and every detail comes alive under this natural glow.

Seeing the Taj Mahal at dawn is more than just a visual experience; it's deeply emotional. The monument, built as a testament to Shah Jahan's undying love for his wife Mumtaz Mahal, evokes feelings of timelessness, loss, and beauty. As the sun continues to rise, the colors of the sky shift from pale blues to warm oranges, wrapping the Taj in a soft embrace that seems almost heavenly.

To truly understand the allure of the Taj Mahal, one must experience this sacred moment. It's not just a wonder of architecture but a place where nature and artistry come together, leaving you with a sense of awe and peace that lingers long after the sun has fully risen.

name: Globe_trotter_ish
review_text:
This is one of the wonders of the world ! Totally recommend to visit this monument if you are near or in Agra !

Wheelchair/ stroller accessible 
Beautiful monument
Clean surroundings
 Best time to visit is early morning or evenings during sunset
 Food and other edible items are not allowed inside the gate
 Drinking water allowed and available inside
Make sure you wear comfortable shoes as there is lots of walking 

 Expect spending 1 -2 hrs here.

 Prices are reasonable. For prices check the website. The monument is open from 30 min before the sunrise to 30min past the sunset.

 A golf cart is available for those who do not wish to walk much at minimal prices.

 Lots of monkeys in that area to beware and avoid eye contact or taking food items with you.

Tour Guides available inside on paid basis.

name: David Delgado
review_text:
The Taj is everything you expect it to be, if you go at the right time. You HAVE to BE there at 05:00 a.m. (gates open at 05:45 a.m.) if you want to have gorgeous views and pics but most importantly, if you want to explore the place calmly without crowds. It's well organized. Buy the tickets online before hand, and you will be ok. Beware of all the "photographers" and tour guides trying to sell you their services. Beware also that the museum that comes with the ticket price, only open at 09:00 so if you are there at 05:00 it will be a long wait (and you cannot get in food or beverages other than water).

name: Rishabh Kumar
review_text:
The entry fee of Taj Mahal is 50 per person for Indian citizens and 540 for SAARC and BIMSTEC citizens. Other foreign visitors need to pay 1100 each. And if you wish to enter the mausoleum, an additional 200 per person is charged. The audio guide is also charged extra.

Here are the ticket prices for the Taj Mahal:
Indian tourists: INR 45
SAARC and BIMSTEC countries: INR 535
Foreigners: INR 1050
Mausoleum entry: INR 200 more
Main ticket with mausoleum entry for foreigners: INR 1250
BIMSTEC or SAARC nation entry ticket with mausoleum fee: INR 735
Children under 15

The Taj Mahal is a white marble mausoleum in Agra, India, built by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan as a tomb for his wife, Mumtaz Mahal
Location
The Taj Mahal is located on the south bank of the Yamuna River in Agra, India.
Architecture
The Taj Mahal is considered a masterpiece of Indo-Islamic architecture, which is a blend of Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles.
Construction
Construction of the Taj Mahal began around 1632 and took 22 years to complete. The complex was built in stages, with the mausoleum itself essentially finished by 1643
Features
The Taj Mahal complex includes the tomb, a mosque, a guest house, a main gate, and four minarets. The mausoleum is set on a high marble plinth, and has four identical facades, each with a central arch 108 ft (33 m) high
Significance
The Taj Mahal is a symbol of love, purity, spirituality, and harmony. It is also a message about the importance of peace and love
UNESCO World Heritage Site
The Taj Mahal was designated a UNESCO World Heritage site in 1983.
Tourism
The Taj Mahal is one of the worlds most iconic monuments and is visited by millions of tourists each year.

name: Joe
review_text: 10/12/24, I came to India this time just for the Taj Mahal. I left the hotel at 5:30 in the morning and arrived at the Taj Mahal quickly. There will be fewer people entering from the other side door, so you can enter earlier. At sunrise, the white marble will have different reflections of light, because there is a tour guide who knows what special photos to take at which points. It takes about two hours to take pictures and browse. You need to go through security before entering, and you cant bring a lot of things. Remember to ask the tour guide. Food or other electronic items are not allowed to be brought in. The ticket is 1,300 rupees. I asked the travel agency to buy it for me first. He sent a file with a QR Code in it. Use the QR Code to scan it. can enter

name: Sujith Mathew
review_text:
Heres some travel information for visiting the Taj Mahal:

*Essentials:*

1. Location: Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India
2. Opening Hours: Sunrise to Sunset (closed on Fridays)
3. Best Time to Visit: October to March (cool weather)
4. Entry Fee: 1100 (approx. $15 USD) per person

*Tips:*

1. Buy tickets online in advance to avoid long queues.
2. Hire a guide for insightful information about the monuments history and architecture.
3. Wear comfortable shoes and clothes.
4. Respect local customs and dress modestly.
5. No eating or drinking allowed inside.

*Getting There:*

1. By Air: Agra Airport (AGR)
2. By Train: Agra Cantonment Station (AGC)
3. By Road: Agra is connected to major cities via national highways.

*Accommodation:*

1. Luxury hotels: Oberoi Amarvilas, The Taj Hotel
2. Budget options: Guesthouses, hostels

*Other Attractions:*

1. Agra Fort
2. Fatehpur Sikri
3. Akbars Tomb

Please note: Prices and information may vary depending on the season and other factors.

name: sunanda thatte
review_text:
As soon as we entered the East Gate,we went to the ticket window, bought the tickets,hired a government appointed guide and made our way to see the Taj.
We had visited after quite a few years!
The first glimpse of the Taj is at the entrance of the Main Gate and its enchanting!
The whole area around it is very well maintained.
The guide took us around in a very systematic way, explained quite a few things about the beautiful.historical monument!
The beauty and symmetry of the monument takes ones breath away!
Its indeed an architectural wonder!
It was heartening to see Good toilet and drinking water facilities.
We felt the guide fees of rupees thousand to be a bit exorbitant.
The guides need to update their knowledge of the history and architecture of the monument.

name: Imtiyaz Ahmed
review_text:
Since childhood, I have seen the Taj Mahal in books, movies, and, of course, toys as well. When I saw the dome of the Taj Mahal from outside before entering the main gate, it was a once-in-a-lifetime moment that was truly unforgettable. Words cannot express the beauty of that sight.

It is surreal when you enter from the main gate and see the Taj Mahal receding from your sight, The view was truly magnificent. Once inside, I sat on the floor and gazed at the Taj Mahal for over an hour without moving.

However, the place was overcrowded with many .People were striking funny poses for photographers. One funny example is trying to imitate the famous pose of raising one hand and touching the tip of the Taj Mahal .

Despite this, the Taj Mahal offers a variety of experiences - from a sense of peace when ignoring the chaos around you, to moments of joy when observing the surroundings, and even situations that could potentially make you angry. It is a place where you can never feel bored.

Although I am not sharing my experience with scammers around the Taj Mahal because everyone might be aware of that issue.

name: Deepak Meher
review_text:
Is it possible to give ratings to Taj. Its just mesmerizing. Though people around arent that polite and helpful. First of all, the taxi drivers, they said there is no place near the monument to keep your luggage, so you have to keep your luggage with us and pay extra. When we reached there was free cloakroom near the monument.

Things didnt end here. Inside the monument a so called photographer said he is certified, clicked random photos and charged us 20 per photo and trust me not a single photo was worth it. We had clicked far better photos in our phones. He charged us around 700 for some unwanted photos.

I would like to say one thing, what do you people gain by cheating tourists around the world for a mere 100 rupees. You would earn a little extra but spoil the travelers whole mood and excitement.

Just felt disgusted.
The photos Im uploading are all clicked by me on my phone. Because I had deleted the ones I had paid for.

name: SAMIR PRAMANIK (Sam)
review_text:
A Masterpiece of Love and Architecture

Review:

The Taj Mahal is a breathtaking testament to the power of love and human ingenuity. Its intricate marble facade, adorned with delicate floral carvings and calligraphy, is a sight to behold. The symmetrical design and the play of light and shadow create a mesmerizing atmosphere.
While the crowds can be significant, especially during peak tourist seasons, the experience is still unforgettable. The early morning hours offer a more serene and less crowded visit, allowing you to truly appreciate the monuments beauty.
A guided tour can provide valuable insights into the history and architecture of the Taj Mahal. Dont miss the opportunity to explore the surrounding gardens, which are equally stunning and offer a peaceful respite from the bustling city.

Tips for visitors:
* Plan your visit: Consider visiting during the off-peak seasons (November to February or July to August) to avoid large crowds.
* Dress appropriately: Modest clothing is required, and avoid wearing shorts or sleeveless tops.
* Carry necessary items: Bring sunscreen, water, and comfortable shoes.
* Respect the monument: Adhere to the rules and regulations, and refrain from touching the marble surfaces.

Overall, the Taj Mahal is a must-see destination for anyone visiting India. Its timeless beauty and historical significance make it a truly unforgettable experience.

name: Konstantin Aushev
review_text:
I believe there are places in India that are evenly beautiful and that have a much more inspiring atmosphere. Yes, the building is impressive, but the overall organisation, infrastructure around do now enable one to feel the place. Yes, the government tries to put some measures to prevent the landmark from dust and mud by banning the gasoline transport around or by fighting the plastic, but still - one should squeeze through crowded dirty streets, rusty gates, not talking about the city nearby. Even the history of the building is, for me, quite far from creating a positive mood. The poor girl was giving birth to another child every 1.5 years during her best years, for the 18th time she died and only after that her husband finally decided to build a home for her, and this construction bankrupted the country. I would not recommend coming specially just for a one-day tour from Delhi. Only if you decide to stay somewhere nearby on the way to another place - then you will probably come by early morning, and will have other feelings than me.

name: Shatadeep Banerjee
review_text:
As one of the seven wonders of the world, it receives a lot of tourists even in the off season. Your best bet is to go at sunrise when there are few tourists and you will have ample time to walk all over the grounds and take photos. I went there around 8:30 AM in early October, and it was already crowded.
Enter from the east gate. Thats where most of the hotels, restaurants, shops and guides are.
Do get a registered tour guide, but only outside the ticket counter, not from anywhere else. You can negotiate with them.
If you want to get professional photos inside, each hard copy would cost you INR 100, while each soft copy would cost you INR 80. However, the number of pictures you get taken could easily reach 100, so keep that in mind.
Get the ticket for the mausoleum as well, the design inside is stunning.

Weekend

name: Ujjawal
review_text:
Over the centuries the Taj Mahal has been subject to neglect and decay. A major restoration was carried out at the beginning of the 20th century under the direction of Lord Curzon, then the British viceroy of India. More recently, air pollution caused by emissions from foundries and other nearby factories and exhaust from motor vehicles has damaged the mausoleum, notably its marble facade. A number of measures have been taken to reduce the threat to the monument, among them the closing of some foundries and the installation of pollution-control equipment at others, the creation of a parkland buffer zone around the complex, and the banning of nearby vehicular traffic. A restoration and research program for the Taj Mahal was initiated in 1998. Progress in improving environmental conditions around the monument has been slow, however.

From time to time the Taj Mahal has been subject to India's political dynamics. Night viewing was banned there between 1984 and 2004 because it was feared that the monument would be a target of Sikh militants. In addition, it increasingly has come to be seen as an Indian cultural symbol. Some Hindu nationalist groups have attempted to diminish the importance of the Muslim influence in accounting for the origins and design of the Taj Mahal.

name: Shambhu Singh
review_text:
Taj Mahal
*Location:* Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India

*Built by:* Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan

*Dedicated to:* Mumtaz Mahal, Shah Jahans wife

*Construction:* 1631-1648

*Architecture:* Mughal and Indo-Islamic style

*Materials:* White marble, red sandstone, and black marble

*Features:*

- Main Dome: 24.5 meters high and 24.5 meters wide
- Four Minarets: Each 130 feet tall
- Reflecting Pool: 580 meters long and 40 meters wide
- Mosque and Guest House: Made of red sandstone
- Charbagh Gardens: Divided into four quadrants

*Significance:*

- Symbol of eternal love and beauty
- Represents the wealth and power of the Mughal Empire
- UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1983

*Interesting Facts:*

- Changes color with the sun: pinkish in morning, white during day, golden in evening
- 28 types of precious and semi-precious stones used
- 22 years of construction
- 20,000 workers involved
- Cost: approximately 32 million rupees (at that time)

*Visiting Information:*

- Timings: sunrise to sunset (closed on Fridays)
- Entry Fee: 1100 (foreigners), 50 (Indians)
- Best Time to Visit: October to February
- Guided Tours: available in multiple languages

*Conservation Efforts:*

- Ongoing restoration to preserve the monument
- Pollution control measures
- Tourism management to reduce impact

*Dimensions:*

- Height: 73 meters (240 feet)
- Length: 186 meters (610 feet)
- Width: 93 meters (305 feet)

*Other Attractions:*

- Agra Fort
- Fatehpur Sikri
- Akbars Tomb
- Mughal Museum

The Taj Mahal is an awe-inspiring monument that attracts millions of visitors each year. Its stunning architecture, beautiful gardens, and rich history make it a must-visit destination in India.

name: TUSHAR KUMAR
review_text:
No wonder its a wonder, Absolutely magnificent.
Entry time:- 30 minutes before Sunrise to 30 minutes before sunset.
Entry from East and West gate only.
Clock room available but they will charge 30 rs for big bags, small bags are free of cost.
The ticket price is 50 for Taj mahal and additional 200 for the main mausoleum you will get a 5 rs discount on the online ticket.
Try do visit in the forenoon. Too much heat so do carry a hat and water bottle with you, water tap is available inside.
The shopkeeper outside will ask you to buy shoe covers but dont buy it because it is available in the Taj mahal for free.
Tip:- You will not get any sharing auto for Taj mahal or any other monuments in agra so if you are solo then book rapido bike taxi which is cheaper than the reserved autos.
Note:- Monday Closed

review_text:
Beautiful place! I visited the Taj Mahal between 10 AM and 12 PM. While the monument itself is breathtaking, I realized this might not be the best time to visit. Early mornings or evenings are probably more pleasant as it was quite sunny during my visit.
A quick note on the tickets: there are two options - 50 and 250. The 250 ticket includes access to the mausoleum, but personally, I didn't find it worth the extra cost. Overall, a must-visit, but plan your timing and ticket choice accordingly!

name: Ajay_ goswami
review_text:
Construction of the mausoleum was completed in 1648, but work continued on other phases of the project for another five years. The first ceremony held at the mausoleum was an observance by Shah Jahan, on 6 February 1643, of the 12th anniversary of the death of Mumtaz Mahal. The Taj Mahal complex is believed to have been completed in its entirety in 1653 at a cost estimated at the time to be around 5 million, which in 2023 would be approximately 35 billion (US$77.8 million) VB The Taj Mahal was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983 for being the jewel of Islamic art in India and one of the universally admired masterpieces of the worlds heritage. It is regarded as one of the best examples of Mughal architecture and a symbol of Indian history. The Taj Mahal is a major tourist attraction and attracts more than five million visitors a year. In 2007, it was declared a winner of the New 7 Wonders of the World initiative.

name: PARAMJEET SINGH KALSI
review_text:
We got down in the car parking at the West gate of Taj Mahal, where some e-rickshaw pullers surrounded us and said that they will charge  160 from four people for going to the gate and visiting Meena Bazaar.
, I told my friends that we should first ride on the R-cart of the tourist department, but we were trapped in the sweet language of the e-rickshaw drivers. That e-rickshaw driver took us from the West Gate back to the Main Road and then through the narrow streets and dropped us at the East Gate. During this entire journey, mine and my friends knees collided with other e-rickshaws many times. Had they collided, we would have had to spend a few days in the hospital and it is not known how long we would be able to walk properly.
My request to everyone is that the best way to go to Taj Mahal is from the West Gate and to go inside from the parking here, use the e-cart of the tourist department which has about 12 seats. And whenever you travel anywhere by e-rickshaw etc., do not take your feet out of the e-rickshaw at all. Otherwise any serious accident can happen to you. And if you go by purchasing the ticket online, it will be even better, you will not have to stand in line for the ticket.
Jai Hind Jai Bharat 
Visited on
Weekend

Wait time
Up to 10 min

Reservation recommended
Yes

name: Rohit Rao
review_text:
my first visit to any wonders of the world and the photos indicate it is the wonder of the world.
Park your vehicle in the government authorised parking and take a golf buggy which charges Rs. 20 from parking to the main entrance gate. Get the tickets either from agents by paying Rs 20-25 per ticket extra or you can get the tickets on your own by booking online through the Taj Mahal online booking portal and that is a very easy process. You have two options to buy tickets either for Rs. 50 or Rs. 245. For Rs 50 you will get entry to the Taj Mahal area but I will recommend you to buy the ticket for Rs 245 which will give you access to enter the Taj Mahal and there you can see the burial of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan and the actual view of Taj Mahal premises.

name: Himanshu Das
review_text:
Its really a symbol of Love! The monument is well maintained, no pictography allowed inside the Taj Mahal. You have to wear shoe cover, either purchase it before hand or it is also available in the premises. Tickets are worth 50 INR for Indian citizens to enter the premises and 250 for access to the Taj Mahal. There is a generally a wait of up to 30 minutes. Earlier the better! You can buy tickets inside, not so crowded, I would not ask you to buy tickets beforehand but definitely would recommend an early morning visit. The sunrise behind the Taj is just mesmerizing!

review_text:
The Taj Mahal is even more majestic in person than in photos--truly a breathtaking sight! However, the ticket price for entering the mausoleum is QR 200, which I found a bit high. One thing to note is that you'll need shoe covers or you'll have to carry your shoes in hand, as they don't sell covers inside, so it's best to bring them from outside. There's also a Taj Museum worth visiting, but be aware that its hours are from 9 AM to 5 PM, which differs from the Taj Mahal's visiting hours.

name: Y T
review_text:
This tomb was built by Shah Jahan, the fifth emperor of the Mughal Empire, for his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal, who died in 1631.

He was trying to build a grave of the same shape as his wifes, whom he loved enough to build such a wonderful grave, on the opposite bank in black marble, but that wish did not come true (;;)

Unparalleled beauty, registered as a World Heritage Site
It is said that Shahjahan built it as a symbol of his eternal love for his beloved wife.
Registered as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983.
A masterpiece of Indian architecture that combines Mughal culture and Islamic art!

I dont think anyone goes to India and leaves without seeing this place.
You should go!
Baggage checks are strict, so bags larger than A4 size are prohibited, and battery-related items are also prohibited. Shoe covers and a bottle of water are available with the ticket purchase.
There is an additional fee to enter the Taj Mahal.

name: Vineet Singh
review_text: Shah Jahan built Taj Mahal in the memory of his wife Mumtaz . When Shah Jahan was 14 years old, He saw Mumtaz which was then 13 years old at Meena Bazar, Shah Jahan took Jahangirs permission to marry Mumtaz. The construction Started in 1631 and it was completed in 1648, again the construction continued for 5 more years and finally it was completed in 1653. Shah Jahan lost Mumtaz when she was delivering her 14th Child in 1631, It is one among the New 7 wonders of the world. It is a UNESCO World Heritage Site, and a total of 20,000 workers were involved in the construction of this beautiful Mahal

name: T. GeBrim
review_text:
The white appearance of the marble turns yellow, brown or green. This is caused by air pollution, insect droppings and construction work in the area.

The water quality of the nearby Yamuna River is severely polluted, leading to a massive infestation of insects, which in turn contaminate the buildings.

The low water level of the Yamuna River has caused the foundations of the Taj Mahal to dry out and become brittle.

name: K S
review_text:
Splendid temple of love. When we know the history and see this architectural marvel, we say to ourselves that love exists!
It is a mausoleum but truly extraordinary. There is no paint, everything is white marble with inlaid stones which give shine.
I agree with other comments which indicate that, although we know the Taj Mahal by name and photo, nothing beats arriving through the main gate, walking a little and discovering this monument. It looks like a 3D photograph in suspense!
It's truly incredible!
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
No
review_translated_text:
Splendide temple de l'amour. Quand on connait l'histoire et qu'on voit cette merveille d'architecture, on se dit que l'amour existe !

C'est un mausolee mais vraiment extraordinaire. Il n'y a pas de peinture tout est en marbre blanc avec des pierres incrustees qui donne de la brillance.

Je rejoins d'autres commentaires qui indiquent que, bien qu'on connaisse le Taj Mahal de nom et en photo, rien de vaut l'arrivee par la grande porte, marcher un peu et decouvrir ce monument. On dirait une photographie en 3D en suspens !

C'est vraiment incroyable !

name: Muhammad Abdur Rahim
review_text:
The Taj Mahal (Hindi: ttaaj mhl, Urdu: taaj mhl) is a royal mausoleum located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India. Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan built this magnificent monument in memory of his wife Arjumand Banu Begum, also known as Mumtaz Mahal. The construction of the monument started in 1632 AD and was completed around 1653 AD.
The Taj Mahal (sometimes simply called the Taj) is considered a striking example of Mughal architecture, combining Persian, Turkish, Indian and Islamic architecture. Although the white marble domed royal mausoleum is the most admired, the Taj Mahal is actually a complex monolithic structure as a whole. It was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983. The Taj Mahal is one of the Seventh Wonders of the World. It was then called the Universally Acclaimed Masterpiece of World Heritage.

name: Damage Case
review_text:
An experience that youd like to never wish to go through again.

If youre reading this, you will obviously go there. So try to go in peak winters, otherwise its hell due to the heat (along with other issues).

Get your tickets online beforehand as its easier. No timing issue. It has multiple gates. The metro station gate is packed with crowds so take an e rickshaw and take the south gate. Official guides are 1800 bucks so people take cheaper ones.

You cant take much stuff inside so get it submitted outside and take a token. The entry queue is the worst hell ever. First you get yourself checked, then put your bag on the belt. Then they put your bags on a table where other hundreds of bags are kept and then starts a big crowd fight to get it checked by security by hand. They will embarrassingly open up ladies/gents bags and purses and check everything one by one. You can imagine how much time one by one bag checking would take! People are screaming and shouting in crowds and fighting to get their bags checked quickly.

There are no canopies or shades. In heat you will burn yourself while walking. The monument is majestic no doubt but only go there in winters. Guides and photographers will make matters worse. They will irritate you.

If you are planning to visit the mausoleum, then skip it if youre not a history buff. The cost of ticket is extra. You cant take pictures inside it. Its not that big. And you have to wait in line to get shoe covers and pay 10 bucks each for it.

Overall its a money making monument with torturous management. If nothing else, at least put some shades around the walking path. Im sure the photographers and guides that are inside are paying hefty bribes to the management otherwise how come they can make their business without paying for tickets etc.

Only go on the weekends (its closed on Fridays). And only go in winters, if you have to!
Visited on
Weekend

Wait time
10-30 min

Reservation recommended
Yes

name: vitikrater
review_text:
I was traveling with a guide, which theoretically wouldnt be necessary once you reach the ticket counter. Tomorrow at 5:50 a.m. no queue for tickets, be sure to book the mausoleum (200 rupees more, total 1300 rupees for foreigners) so that you can get to the upper platform in front of the Taj. You get a bottle of water and shoe covers at a second counter. Other drinks and food would not be taken. Entry at the West Gate takes less than a minute at 6 a.m. From 7 a.m. it became noticeably more crowded. Great, spacious facility - no more harassment from salespeople inside. You can find all the paths on your own, the tour is self-explanatory. With lots of pictures, 1.5 hours is sufficient.
Visited on
Weekend

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
Yes
review_translated_text: Ich war mit Guide unterwegs, was theoretisch aber nicht notig ware, sobald man den Ticketschalter erreicht. Morgen um 5:50 Uhr keine Schlange fur Tickets, unbedingt das Mausoleum mitbuchen (200 Rupien mehr, insgesamt 1300 Rupien fur Auslander), damit man auch auf die obere Plattform vor dem Taj kommt. Man bekommt eine Flasche Wasser und Schuhuberzieher an einem zweiten Schalter. Andere Getranke und Essen wurden nicht mitgenommen werden. Einlass am West Gate dauert um 6 Uhr keine Minute. Ab 7 Uhr wurde es deutlich voller. Tolle, weitlaufige Anlage - innen auch keine Belastigung mehr durch Verkaufer. Man findet alle Wege auch alleine, die Fuhrung ist selbsterklarend. Mit vielen Bildern sind 1,5 Std. ausreichend.

name: Avinendra Pahunchel
review_text:
How incredible is Ustad Lahoris architecture. The construction project employed more than 22,000 workers and artisans under the guidance of Ustad Ahmad Lahori. The Taj Mahal complex is believed to have been completed in its entirety in 1653 at a cost estimated at the time to be around 5 million, which in 2023 would be approximately 35 billion. The Taj Mahal was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983. It is regarded as one of the best examples of Mughal architecture and a symbol of Indian history.

name: Abhijeet Mishra
review_text: Visiting the Taj Mahal was a breathtaking experience! The beauty of the white marble structure is beyond words, especially at sunrise when the monument glows softly. The intricate details of the carvings and the symmetry of the gardens make it a photographer's paradise. As you walk closer, the craftsmanship becomes even more mesmerizing. The history and love story behind it add an emotional depth to the visit. Be prepared for crowds, but the experience is absolutely worth it. Its truly a symbol of Indias rich heritage and architectural brilliance! A must-see for anyone visiting India.

name: Jason Peck
review_text:
Group visited on a Monday.
Early for the sunrise. No queues as such.
Electric vehicles from the drop off point to the entry point. Buy tickets and then through security screening. Double check the list of things you cannot bring in.
As a group, we got a photographer who took all of our group photos. Cost is IDR$100 per photo or in bulk deal and you get paper photo and electronic copy as well.
Both the long distance wide angle photo and from the Diana seat. Well worth it.
We chose to go barefoot on the marble instead of wearing the shoe covers. It felt so good to be walking on such hallowed grounds in bare feet.
Awesome and truly amazing place.
Highly recommend to everyone.
Note : There are hawkers inside the grounds who will help with photos or provide artistic guidance for a tip.
Nice to walk around the whole grounds and enjoy the experience.
It gets much busier after sunrise, and is busy all day.

name: piyush yadav
review_text:
The Taj Mahal!

One of the Seven Wonders of the Modern World and a UNESCO World Heritage Site, the Taj Mahal is an iconic white marble mausoleum in Agra, India.

*History:*

Built between 1632 and 1653 by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan as a tribute to his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal, who died during childbirth.

*Architecture:*

- Blends Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles
- Symmetrical design with intricate inlays of precious stones
- Reflecting pools and gardens add to its beauty

*Interesting Facts:*

1. Took 22,000 workers and 1,000 elephants to build
2. Cost: approximately 32 million rupees (about $450 million today)
3. Changes color with the light: pinkish in sunrise, white in daytime, and golden in sunset
4. Made from Makrana white marble
5. Surrounding complex includes mosques, gardens, and fountains

*Visiting Information:*

1. Location: Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India
2. Open: Sunrise to sunset (closed on Fridays)
3. Best time to visit: October to February
4. Ticket prices: vary depending on nationality and time of day

*Symbolism:*

The Taj Mahal represents eternal love, beauty, and romance, attracting millions of visitors worldwide.

name: RICARDO PALMAS
review_text:
You are left without words to define such a sublime work. For me it is without a doubt the most beautiful construction made by human beings. Its magic leaves you hypnotized and you would spend hours contemplating that beauty that has no parallel in the world.
They must have told you. You will have seen it millions of times in photographs, documentaries, etc., but until you see it with your own eyes you wont believe it.
Especially first thing in the morning it seems like a mirage.....
review_translated_text:
Te quedas sin palabras para definir esa obra tan sublime. Para mi es sin duda la mas bonita construccion hecha por el ser humano. Su magia te deja hipnotizado y te pasarias horas contemplando esa belleza que no tiene parangon en el mundo.

Te lo habran contado. Lo habras visto millones de veces en fotografias, documentales, etc, pero hasta que no lo contemplas con tus propios ojos no te lo crees.

Sobre todo a primera hora de la manana parece un espejismo.....

name: Mohammed Shahim
review_text:
Words cannot describe the beauty of this place, unfortunately it merely gets ruined by so called government approved guides who try to scam every rupee from you. As soon as we got to the Taj Mahal, we were approached by a guide who instantly took us to book online tickets and used his phone number to get the online tickets. I advised home we dont need a guide and just want to enjoy the Taj Mahal by ourselves but we were constantly pressured. He then took us to the golf carts, who drive for like 10 meters then stopped and asked us all to pay, then when we got to the security check area they took our bags away from us and told us to go back to the male section and go through the body scanner. Then the police made remarks that other police in hindi that because we were foreigners we should be checked more thoroughly, i asked why as were from Australia and our security is more strict, then they put all my things back in my bags and let us go through. At the first point the guide spoke for about 5 minutes, I stopped him and said we dont need a guide and that he needs to stop pressuring us. I gave him 500 rupees and told him to leave us alone and he started hassling us and said we should have told him right at the beginning, I told I tried to tell you at the beginning but you did not want to listen. After he left us alone, we enjoyed a nice 1 hour walk admiring the majestic Taj Mahal and the surrounding grounds. We also paid the extra 200rupees to go inside the mausoleum but when you get to the entrance then to get the blue shoe cover its 50rupees each.

It is a shame that India has such fascinating monuments, culture and history but it all gets ruined by scammers. The government should get involved and make all these places a better place without allowing scammers to stay active.

name: Vellesya
review_text:
My husband and i visited the Taj Mahal for our honeymoon in April and it was such a surreal experience

Pro:
April/May is summer, so there weren't too many people!  We could soak in the beauty without the usual massive crowds

Con:
It's HOT. Like, seriously HOT!  Be ready for the sun and heat, especially if you're there later in the day. Bring a hat or sunscreen 

We got our tickets on the spot --1,100 rupees for Southeast Asian tourists like us  It includes a super helpful tour guide & bottled water 

We got there bright and early at 5 AM to catch the sunrise & it was magical! 

Since it was so early, the place was practically less crowded. As the day went on, it did get busier, so the early bird definitely gets the best views 

Our tour guide gave us all the details about the Taj Mahal's history --from how it was built to all the little stories that made it so special

Seeing the Taj Mahal in person is a whole other level. It's so much bigger and more beautiful than we ever imagined . The surrounding gardens are gorgeous too --perfect for taking a little break in the shade

Afterward, our guide took us to a souvenir shop . It was a bit pricey , and they claimed the items were made with stones used in the Taj Mahal itself. We couldn't resist and bought something, but by the time we got back to home, it had cracked 

Overall, it was such an unforgettable experience

Visiting the Taj Mahal was an incredible experience! As one of the Seven Wonders of the World, it truly lives up to its reputation. The beauty and serenity of the Taj Mahal are unparalleled--its a sight to behold and a peaceful retreat.

The security is tight, which is reassuring given the number of visitors. The complex is well-maintained, though it can get crowded, especially with photographers trying to capture the perfect shot. It costs 30 for a single photo, and you might end up spending quite a bit if you want multiple shots.

Entry to the Taj Mahal costs 50, and if you want to visit the tomb inside, theres an additional charge of 250. Despite these costs, the experience is well worth it. The majesty of the monument and the historical significance make it a must-visit for anyone traveling to India. Highly recommended for anyone interested in history, architecture, or simply appreciating an iconic piece of heritage!

name: Sankha Chakraborty
review_text:
Visiting the Taj Mahal was a breathtaking experience that lived up to its reputation as one of the most stunning architectural marvels in the world. From the moment I arrived, I was struck by t sheer beauty and grandeur of this iconic monument.

The Taj Mahal's pristine white marble facade, adorned with intricate inlay work, is nothing short of mesmerizing. The symmetry and craftsmanship are exquisite, reflecting the incredible artistry and dedication of its creators. The surrounding gardens, reflecting pools, and the serene Yamuna River add to the monument's allure, providing a picturesque backdrop that enhances the overall experience.

Walking through the mausoleum and gazing at the detailed marble inlays and carvings was a profound experience. The interior, where Emperor Shah Jahan and his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal are entombed, is as beautiful and serene as the exterior.

The best time to visit is early in the morning or late in the afternoon when the light creates a stunning play of colors on the marble, adding to the monument's ethereal quality. The staff and guides are knowledgeable and enhance the visit with rich historical context and insights.

Overall, a visit to the Taj Mahal is a must for anyone interested in history, architecture, or simply experiencing one of the worlds most beautiful places. It's a remarkable testament to love and an unforgettable journey into India's rich cultural heritage.

name: KOUSIK PARIA
review_text:
The Taj Mahal, located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, is an iconic symbol of Indias rich cultural and architectural heritage. Recognized globally for its stunning beauty, this UNESCO World Heritage Site was commissioned by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in the 17th century as a mausoleum for his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal.

The Taj Mahal's architectural grandeur is breathtaking. Its white marble facade, adorned with intricate inlays and detailed carvings, exudes a timeless elegance. The central dome, surrounded by lush gardens, reflecting pools, and four minarets, creates a harmonious and majestic visual impression. The symmetry and meticulous design exemplify Mughal architectural brilliance and craftsmanship.

Visitors to the Taj Mahal are often captivated by its serene atmosphere and the emotional depth of its backstory. Early mornings and late afternoons are particularly recommended for viewing, as the play of light enhances the marble's shimmering quality and the surrounding landscape's beauty.

However, the site does face some challenges. It can become extremely crowded, particularly during peak tourist seasons, which might detract from the experience. Additionally, the surrounding area has seen increasing commercial development, which some visitors find less appealing. Efforts to manage crowds and maintain the site's pristine condition are ongoing, but improvements in visitor management could enhance the overall experience.

In summary, the Taj Mahal remains a monumental testament to love and architectural excellence. Despite some challenges related to crowd management and commercialization, its enduring beauty and historical significance make it a must-visit landmark for anyone traveling to India.

name: Adrian Yeong
review_text:
While driving in toward the parking , I got stopped by a guide on a motorbike.
Telling me that the waiting time to go in might take 45 - 60 mins.
If I use him, no waiting time and everything will be express. He quoted me 1800 rupee and it was raining at that time. Wanted to use him but in the end , he bought me to a parking place that need to pay 100 rupee and after that I decided not to because before he told me that parking is free.

After that , I managed to park at the area where the electric bungee were and paid 20 rupee for the bungee to get in to the ticket counter. Upon arriving at the parking , there are a lot more guides knocking at my door.
Some charges 200 rupee to get tickets for me.
Some asking for 500 rupee as a guide. But I had rejected all and took the bungee in.
There was no Q at all at the counter and the process was fast.
A lot of people there trying to be nice to help me guide the way , sell umbrella , rent , or even pass me the umbrella but after that wanted me to go to their shops.
But I had rejected all and decided to just walk in the rain.
Process for checking the bags and body checks was chaotic. No food allowed , I had sweets in my bag and was asked to throw. I had a talisman that I bought at leh which was forbidden to bring in and I threw it away during the check too.
After that , it's the walk and the majestic view.
Its was raining and windy.
And I think that there would be more people if there was no rain.
When everything is finish , going back out , I got to face the shops owners asking me to go in their shops and the waiting for the bungee ride are in a mess.
But somehow I managed to get up 1 and this time I didn't pay anything. I don't know why.
But I am grateful that I am able to witness everything and was safe.
Hope I can help people who want to come here to understand more of how the process is like.
And the ticket is 1300 rupee including the walk in the museum. I advise to get them too rather then just paying 1100 rupee to go in.

name: Pooja
review_text:
It would be an understatement if I try to explain the beauty of the Taj Mahal!
It is a masterpiece which is difficult to re-create with the same intricacies and finesse.
Not only the Taj Mahal, but the entire area is well maintained with greenery all around and cleanliness is also fully maintained.
When we visited, all the water bodies were without water as there was some cleaning project happening, but still it did not impact the beauty of the giant marble structure.
It is recommended to visit in the first half of the day or early mornings are much better to avoid unwanted crowds and to appreciate the real magnificence.
If one wants to go inside the massive building, there are separate tickets of 200 and 250 and need to buy disposable shoe covers from the counter or lot of hawkers selling it outside for 10 for each pair. Though reusable ones are available too, but they are filthy and smelling. Entry tickets are for 40 each and children can visit for free.
If you get a chance to visit, do not miss the opportunity and show it to the younger generation too.

name: Kc Jeh
review_text:
A Timeless Marvel of Love and Beauty*

The Taj Mahal is an awe-inspiring monument that transcends time and leaves visitors spellbound. This stunning white marble mausoleum, built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal, is a testament to eternal love and architectural excellence.

*Architectural Splendor*

The Taj Mahals perfect proportions, intricate inlays, and calligraphic inscriptions create a sense of harmony and balance. The reflecting pools, gardens, and fountains add to the serene ambiance, making it a haven for peace and contemplation.

*Emotional Connection*

As you step inside, the Taj Mahals emotional resonance is palpable. The story of Shah Jahans love and loss is etched in every stone, making this monument a poignant reminder of the power of love.

A Must-Visit Experience

The Taj Mahal is an absolute must-visit destination for anyone interested in history, architecture, or simply experiencing the beauty of human creation. Be prepared to be mesmerized by its grandeur and left with memories to cherish forever.

My Rating: 5/5 stars
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
10-30 min

name: Dinesh Patil
review_text:
Taj Mahal is Worlds included in 7 wonder. It is situated in Agra City on the bank of the Yamuna river, Uttar Pradesh. It was commissioned in 1631 by the fifth Mughal Emperor. The height of Taj Mahal is 73 m. It is a very beautiful and wonderful view. Lots of foreigners are coming to India to see this beautiful place. I love this place as it is very huge and the construction of the Taj Mahal is very awesome. This is built by Shahajahan for Mumtaz Mahal, his wife. According to a survey it is seen that there are wooden constructions below Taj Mahal because this is situated near the river and due to water this special wood becomes strong. It is a famous spot in the Agra and even in India. This is a very busy tourist place. During the India-Pakistan war this place is covered with bamboo and Cloth to avoid Air strike. A yearly nearly 4.5 million visitors are coming to this place.

name: Kranti k. Verma
review_text:
Best monument of the world.
The Taj Mahal is a symphony of marble and moonlight, a harmony of human emotion and divine beauty. As I stood before its shimmering facade, I felt the weight of love and loss, the tender touch of a emperors devotion to his beloved. The intricate inlays danced like stars in the fading light, and the reflecting pools rippled like the tears of the bereaved. In this mausoleum of wonder, I discovered the transcendent power of art to capture the essence of the human experience. The Taj Mahal is more than a monument - its a whispered promise of eternal love, echoing across the centuries.

name: Dheeraj Kumar Verma
review_text:
A large artisan team was mainly involved in building the Taj Mahal, which included many great artisans. The principal architect and builder was Ustad Ahmed Lahauri, an exemplary Mughal architect who managed the carving and construction structure of the Taj Mahal. He created the unique architectural style of the Taj Mahal and incorporated Mughal culture and architecture as well as traditional Indian styles. Additionally, other artisans were also involved in this work, who were his distinguished assistants and helped in various aspects of the construction. This included a team of residential and non-residential artisans, marble cutting artisans, marble artisans, colorful stitching artisans, carving artisans, lighting artists and jewelers. They worked on marble and stone carving, luminous art, tunneling architecture, silver work, colorful stitching and gold work. The beauty, carvings and intricate craftsmanship of the Taj Mahal symbolize the hard work and skill of the artisans who built this great grandeur.

The full name of Taj Mahal is "Diwan-i-Khas-i-Khusro". This mausoleum was built in memory of Mumtaz Mahal, wife of Mughal emperor Shahjahan. It is also known as "Taj Mahal" in English. "Taj" means "Taj Mahal" and "Mahal" means "mausoleum" or "palace". It means "Taj mausoleum" or "Taj palace". It is one of the major heritage sites of India and is considered as the most amazing architectural decoration of the world.

name: Salman Khan
review_text:
Here are some interesting facts about the Taj Mahal:

1. _Symbol of Love_: The Taj Mahal was built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan as a mausoleum for his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal, who died in childbirth.

2. _Architectural Marvel_: The Taj Mahal is considered one of the greatest examples of Mughal architecture, blending Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles.

3. _White Marble_: The Taj Mahal is made of white Makrana marble, which was brought from over 300 kilometers away.

4. _Precise Geometry_: The Taj Mahals design is based on precise geometric calculations, with perfect symmetry and alignment.

5. _Changing Colors_: The Taj Mahal appears to change colors depending on the time of day and weather, due to the unique properties of the marble.

6. _Intricate Inlays_: The Taj Mahal features intricate inlays of precious stones, including jasper, jade, and turquoise.

7. _Calligraphic Inscriptions_: The Taj Mahal has intricate calligraphic inscriptions from the Quran, which were written by a calligrapher who was paid a single rupee per word.

8. _Garden Design_: The Charbagh garden surrounding the Taj Mahal is designed according to the principles of Islamic garden design, representing the four quadrants of the universe.

9. _Moonlight View_: The Taj Mahal is even more breathtaking under moonlight, when it appears to glow with an ethereal light.

10. _UNESCO World Heritage Site_: The Taj Mahal is a UNESCO World Heritage Site, recognized for its cultural and natural significance.

11. _Costly Construction_: The Taj Mahal took over 22 years to build and cost around 32 million rupees, a staggering amount at the time.

12. _Taj Mahals Secret_: The Taj Mahal has a hidden passageway and a secret room, which are not accessible to the public.

These facts only scratch the surface of the Taj Mahals grandeur and beauty. Visit it to experience its majesty firsthand!

I recommend arriving early to avoid crowds and enjoy the peaceful atmosphere. The gardens are beautifully maintained, and the reflection of the Taj in the water is absolutely magical. The history behind it makes the visit even more profound.

name: Eno Elbika M
review_text: Tak Mahal is a magnificent mausoleum located in Agra, India. Built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in the 17th century as a tribute to his wife, Mumtaz Mahal, this monument is a prime example of Mughal architecture. Tak Mahal is famous for its white dome made of marble, as well as intricate decorations that include carvings and gemstones. The complex consists of manicured gardens, a reflecting pool, and a mosque. Tak Mahal is recognized as one of the wonders of the world and a symbol of eternal love, attracting millions of visitors every year. Its symmetrical architectural beauty and elegant design reflect the refinement of art and building techniques of that time.
review_translated_text: Tak Mahal adalah sebuah mausoleum megah yang terletak di Agra, India. Dibangun oleh Kaisar Mughal Shah Jahan pada abad ke-17 sebagai penghormatan untuk istrinya, Mumtaz Mahal, monumen ini adalah contoh utama arsitektur Mughal. Tak Mahal terkenal dengan kubah putihnya yang terbuat dari marmer, serta dekorasi rumit yang mencakup ukiran dan batu permata. Kompleks ini terdiri dari taman-taman terawat, kolam refleksi, dan masjid. Tak Mahal diakui sebagai salah satu keajaiban dunia dan simbol cinta abadi, menarik jutaan pengunjung setiap tahun. Kecantikan arsitekturnya yang simetris dan desainnya yang elegan mencerminkan kehalusan seni dan teknik bangunan pada masa itu.

name: Shaurya Batham
review_text:
Taj Mahal is a world famous historical monument located in the city of Agra, India. It was built by Mughal emperor Shahjahan in memory of his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal. Taj Mahal is considered a symbol of love and is one of the seven wonders of the world. Its construction began in 1632 and was completed in 1653, taking approximately 22 years to build.

The Taj Mahal is constructed from white marble and its architecture is a beautiful fusion of Mughal, Persian, Turkish and Indian styles. Apart from the main dome, it also has four minarets which further enhance its beauty. The tombs of Mumtaz Mahal and Shahjahan are located inside the Taj Mahal.

Its walls have exquisite carvings and decoration of precious stones, which makes it unique. The beauty of the Taj Mahal situated on the banks of Yamuna river becomes even more captivating when its reflection is seen in the water. Every year lakhs of tourists come from India and abroad to see it. Taj Mahal is not only a heritage of India, but it is also a unique example of art, culture and love.

name: Vikash chauhan youtuber
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is a tomb and monument in Agra, India, built by Mughal emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife, Mumtaz Mahal. The story of the Taj Mahal is one of love, loss, and a desire to create a symbol of purity, spirituality, and harmony:

Love
The Taj Mahal was built as a tomb for Mumtaz Mahal, who was Shah Jahans beloved wife and inseparable companion. Shah Jahan affectionately called her Mumtaz Mahal, which means ornament of the palace. The name Taj Mahal comes from this term of endearment.

Loss
Mumtaz Mahal died in childbirth in 1631, three years after marrying Shah JahanShah Jahan wanted the Taj Mahal to symbolize purity, spirituality, harmony, and solemnity. He intended it to convey the message that Pure love is the soul of life.

Architecture
The Taj Mahal is an example of Mughal architecture, which combines Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles.

World Heritage Site
The Taj Mahal complex was named a UNESCO World Heritage site in 1983.

name: Arnab
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is an ivory-white marble mausoleum on the right bank of the river Yamuna in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India. The tomb is the centrepiece of a 17-hectare (42-acre) complex, which includes a mosque and a guest house, and is set in formal gardens bounded on three sides by a crenellated wall.

While the mausoleum is constructed of white marble inlaid with semi-precious stones, red sandstone was used for other buildings in the complex similar to the Mughal era buildings of the time.
The Taj Mahal was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983 for being the jewel of Islamic art in India and one of the universally admired masterpieces of the worlds heritage. It is regarded as one of the best examples of Mughal architecture and a symbol of Indian history. The Taj Mahal is a major tourist attraction and attracts more than five million visitors a year. In 2007, it was declared a winner of the New 7 Wonders of the World initiative.

name: ALOK KUMAR
review_text:
The Taj Mahal, located in Agra, India, is an iconic symbol of love and one of the most famous landmarks in the world. This exquisite white marble mausoleum, commissioned by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in 1632, stands as a testament to the grandeur of Mughal architecture and the enduring love between Shah Jahan and his wife, Mumtaz Mahal.

**Architecture:**
The Taj Mahals design is a masterpiece of Mughal architecture, blending Persian, Islamic, and Indian styles. Its centerpiece is the stunning white marble dome, which is surrounded by four minarets. The mausoleum is set within a sprawling garden, featuring symmetrical layouts, reflecting pools, and lush greenery, enhancing its serene beauty.

**Significance:**
The Taj Mahal was built as a tomb for Mumtaz Mahal, Shah Jahans beloved wife who passed away during childbirth. The structure not only serves as a tribute to her but also represents the zenith of Mughal architecture. It was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983 for its cultural and architectural significance.

**Visiting Tips:**
- **Best Time to Visit:** Early morning or late afternoon, especially during sunrise or sunset, for the best light and fewer crowds.
- **Tickets:** Purchase tickets in advance online to avoid long queues. There are separate tickets for Indian citizens and international tourists.
- **Dress Code:** Modest clothing is recommended.
- **Photography:** Photography is allowed in designated areas, but tripods and professional cameras may require special permits.
- **Guides:** Hiring a local guide can enrich your visit with historical insights and anecdotes.

The Taj Mahal is not just a monument but a timeless symbol of love and architectural brilliance. Its breathtaking beauty continues to captivate visitors from around the globe, making it a must-see destination for anyone traveling to India.
