name: LUCKY TECH. COM
review_text:
The Taj Mahal (Urdu: tj mHl) is a World Heritage mausoleum located in the city of Agra in the state of Uttar Pradesh, India, and one of the 7 Wonders of the World. It was built in the 17th century by Mughal emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal.[1]

Duration: 10 minutes and 7 seconds.10:07
Taj Mahal incomparable heritage
Mughal architecture was at its peak during the time of Mughal emperor Shahjahan, Taj Mahal is the most famous example of that architecture. Taj Mahal is an excellent example of Mughal architecture. Its architectural style is a unique fusion of elements from Persian, Ottoman, Indian and Islamic architecture. In 1983, the Taj Mahal became a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Along with this, it was described as one of the most universally praised human creations of world heritage. Taj Mahal has also been declared the gem of Islamic art of India. Unlike the commonly seen buildings which are covered with large sheets of marble blocks, its white dome and tiles are covered [2] with marble in shape. The tomb built in the center shows the combination of beauty in its architectural superiority. The special thing about the structure of the Taj Mahal building group is that it is completely symmetrical. Its construction was completed around 1648. [1] Ustad Ahmed Lahauri is often considered its chief designer. [3] It took about 22 years to construct the Taj Mahal.

architecture
Main article: Origins and architecture of Taj Mahal
mausoleum

Map of floor plan of Taj Mahal
The centerpiece of the Taj Mahal is the white marble mausoleum built on a square foundation. It is a symmetrical building, which has an iwan i.e. a very large curved (arch-shaped) door. A large dome adorns the top of this building. Like most Mughal tombs, its basic components are of Persian origin.

basic premise
Its basic foundation is a huge multi-chambered structure. This main chamber is cubic, each side of which is 55 meters (see: floor map, right). On the long sides is a massive pishtaq, or arched-roofed chamber gate. It is connected to the arched balcony above.

main arch
On either side of the main arch, two additional pishtaqs are built on either side, one above the other. In the same style, two pishtaqs (one above the other) are built on all four sides of the chamber. This structure is completely symmetrical on each side of the building, which makes the building an octagon rather than a square, but since the four corner sides are much shorter than the other four sides, it would be appropriate to call it square. The four towers around the tomb seem to frame the view of the building, at the four corners of the original base post. The main chamber contains the fake tombs of Mumtaz Mahal and Shahjahan. These are very decorated, and their original is situated on the lower floor.

name: Muhammad Asif
review_text:
A Timeless Wonder - Taj Mahal.

Rating: 5/5

I recently had the privilege of visiting the Taj Mahal, and I must say, its a truly breathtaking experience. This stunning white marble mausoleum in Agra, India, is a testament to love, beauty, and human ingenuity.

As I stepped through the gates, I was struck by the sheer scale and grandeur of the monument. The intricate inlays, ornate calligraphy, and perfect proportions all combine to create a sense of awe and wonder.

The story of Shah Jahans love for Mumtaz Mahal, which inspired the construction of the Taj, adds a poignant layer of depth to the experience. The monuments perfect blend of Indian, Persian, and Islamic architectural styles is a reflection of the regions rich cultural heritage.

The complex is immaculately maintained, with beautiful gardens and a tranquil atmosphere that belies the crowds. The sunset view, with the golden light casting a warm glow over the marble, is truly unforgettable.

Overall, the Taj Mahal is an absolute must-visit destination for anyone interested in history, architecture, or simply experiencing one of the worlds most iconic wonders.

Pros:

- Breathtaking architecture and design
- Immaculately maintained complex and gardens
- Poignant love story and historical significance
- Perfect blend of Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles
- Unforgettable sunset views

Cons: None

Highlights:

- Intricate inlays and ornate calligraphy
- Perfect proportions and scale
- Tranquil atmosphere and beautiful gardens
- Rich cultural heritage and historical significance
- Unforgettable experience

Tips for visitors:

- Plan ahead and book tickets online to avoid crowds
- Hire a knowledgeable guide to appreciate the history and architecture
- Visit at sunset for the most breathtaking views
- Respect the monuments rules and regulations
- Take your time to absorb the beauty and atmosphere

name: Diego Perez Morales
review_text:
The monument is impressive and the gardens are beautiful, all the marble inlay and carving work is exquisite. Inside there are guides that show you the transparency of the embedded semi-precious stones and the translucency of the Marble. When I went, the Mosque could not be visited since it was under restoration. It is recommended to go early due to the heat and the large influx of people around midday. There is nothing to eat or buy anything. You can only enter with water

name: aditya salvi
review_text:
Visiting the Taj Mahal for the first time is nothing short of a surreal experience. As you approach this iconic monument, the anticipation builds, and the moment you catch your first glimpse of the gleaming white marble, it feels as though youve stepped into a dream. The Taj Mahals ethereal beauty defies words; its sheer size, the intricate details of the carvings, and the symmetry of the entire structure make it a sight to behold.

Upon arrival, you are greeted by helpful local guides, who share fascinating insights into the history and craftsmanship behind the Taj. Their stories bring the monument to life, weaving a narrative of love, loss, and architectural brilliance. They also know the best spots for photographs, helping you capture the magic of the moment.

One of the most thoughtful aspects of the visit is the battery-operated cabs that ferry visitors to and from the parking area. These eco-friendly vehicles ensure that the serene ambiance around the Taj Mahal remains undisturbed by pollution or noise. The short ride through the well-maintained approach road allows you to gather your thoughts and prepare yourself for the awe-inspiring sight that awaits.

As you walk through the grand entrance and the Taj Mahal comes into full view, you cant help but feel a sense of wonder and reverence. The shimmering reflection in the long pool, the peacefulness of the surroundings, and the sheer majesty of the monument create an experience that feels almost otherworldly.

The visit to the Taj Mahal is a journey not just through space, but through time and emotion--a truly surreal experience that stays with you long after youve left.

name: Devesh Gautam
review_text:
Taj Mahal, a symbol of love and beauty! As a local guide, I can tell you:

- Its a stunning white marble mausoleum built by Shah Jahan for his wife Mumtaz Mahal.
- Changes colors with the day and season.
- Features intricate inlays of precious stones.
- Surrounded by the serene Charbagh garden.
- Best visited early morning or late evening to avoid crowds.

Come, let me show you the Tajs secrets and stories! The Taj Mahal is surrounded by several attractions and landmarks in Agra, India. Here are some nearby places to explore:

1. _Agra Fort_: A majestic red sandstone fort and palace, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

2. _Fatehpur Sikri_: A abandoned city and former Mughal capital, known for its well-preserved architecture.

3. _Itmad-Ud-Daulahs Tomb_: A beautiful marble mausoleum, often called the Baby Taj.

4. _Mehtab Bagh_: A charming garden offering stunning views of the Taj Mahal.

5. _Kinari Bazaar_: A bustling marketplace for shopping and trying local street food.

6. _Akbars Tomb_: The final resting place of Mughal Emperor Akbar.

7. _Mariam-uz-Zamanis Tomb_: The tomb of Akbars wife, Mariam-uz-Zamani.

8. _Chini Ka Rauza_: A beautiful mausoleum decorated with glazed tiles.

9. _Taj Museum_: A museum showcasing artifacts and exhibits related to the Taj Mahal.

10. _Yamuna River_: Take a boat ride or stroll along the riverbank for scenic views.

Explore these nearby attractions to get a deeper understanding of Agras rich history and culture!

name: Masashi
review_text:
OBe careful of the guide-like person at the entrance of the Taj Mahal
For Japanese people, when they think of India, they think of curry, Dhalsim from Street Fighter, and one of the most famous things: the Taj Mahal.
Since I went on a tour, I left the purchasing of admission tickets and procedures to the guide.
A guide will accompany you to the viewpoint where you can see the Taj Mahal, but you will have to enter the Taj Mahal alone.
Once inside, a guide-like Indian man will give you a brief explanation in English and then ask for a tip, but there is no need to pay.
The guide had warned me about this beforehand, and I was able to understand it by actually facing it.
You can request a photographer outside to take pictures through the guide, but the guide will take the pictures with his own camera (smartphone), so unless you want to use a good camera, there is no need to ask for one. I thought.

name: Merlin Thomas
review_text:
Shah Jahan built the Taj Mahal in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal. One of the main attractions of the architecture is the symmetry, such as the twin mosques placed symmetrically on either side of the mausoleum, and how it changes color throughout the day depending on how the sun strikes it.
The monument has been designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site, and is one of the Seven Wonders of the World. Inside are the cenotaphs of Mumtaz and Shah Jahan.
The beautiful cenotaphs are actually replicas of actual tombs. Sarcophagi are located under the tombs, at the garden level. It is a myth that Shah Jahan chopped the hands of those in charge of building the Taj Mahal. If you wish to learn more about the history and monuments, you can hire a government-authorized tour guide. A ticket for Indians costs 50/-, but to visit inside the Taj Mahal, you must pay an additional 200/-.

name: JISHNU V S
review_text:
Construction of the mausoleum was completed in 1648, but work continued on other phases of the project for another five years. The first ceremony held at the mausoleum was an observance by Shah Jahan, on 6 February 1643, of the 12th anniversary of the death of Mumtaz Mahal. The Taj Mahal complex is believed to have been completed in its entirety in 1653 at a cost estimated at the time to be around 5 million, which in 2023 would be approximately 35 billion (US$77.8 million).

The building complex incorporates the design traditions of Indo-Islamic and Mughal architecture. It employs symmetrical constructions with the usage of various shapes and symbols. While the mausoleum is constructed of white marble inlaid with semi-precious stones, red sandstone was used for other buildings in the complex similar to the Mughal era buildings of the time. The construction project employed more than 20,000 workers and artisans under the guidance of a board of architects led by Ustad Ahmad Lahori, the emperors court architect.

name: Vikash Rawat
review_text:
I recently visited the Taj Mahal, and it was a great experience. For a first-time visit, the beauty and size of the monument are really impressive. The design and structure are amazing, and its clear why its such a famous site.

Theres also a lot of interesting history to learn about the Taj Mahal, which makes the visit even more worthwhile. Its fascinating to see such an important piece of history in person.

However, I feel that one visit is enough for me. While the Taj Mahal is beautiful and worth seeing, I dont think I would go back a second time.

Overall, I would give my visit 4 out of 5 stars. Its definitely worth going once to see the stunning architecture and to learn about its history.

name: Albin Saji
review_text:
The Taj Mahal in Agra, India has been the subject of many positive reviews. Some people call it a must-see while others describe it as stunning and mesmerizing. Here are some insights from reviews:

Beauty

Most people see the Taj Mahal as architecture and beauty at its best because it changes color during different times of the day.

Time of day

Others say that sun rises up at six am when gates open. It is also said to be a busy place during sunset especially near marble seating.

Photography

It has also been mentioned that photographing inside isn't allowed but outside can be done from a distance. Security personnel will blow whistles on anybody who tries taking photos within the mausoleum's precincts since cameras may also be seized.

Other attractions

They also encourage tourists to visit other places such as Sikandra, Fatehpur Sikri and other tombs of Akbar, Itmad-ud-Daulah's tomb etc in Agra beside famous AgraFort.

name: Umang Dasani
review_text:
Taj Mahal, the name is enough to describe the beauty of ancient architecture. Every time I visit the Taj, I found something new and interesting. The building incorporates the traditional design of Indo-Islamic and Mughal architecture. IThe Taj is also seen from the Red fort. It employs symmetrical constructions with the usage of various shapes and symbols. While the mausoleum is constructed of white marble inlaid with semi-precious stones, red sandstone was used for other buildings in the complex similar to the Mughal era buildings of the time.
The wall of Taj has beautiful design on precious stone and calligraphy over walls. It also has a large beautiful garden to relax and enjoy the beauty of Taj. Its atmosphere is also peaceful due to perfect location on the bank of Yamuna river.
One thing that you may find very strange, but the truth is that the Taj changes its colour three times a day. Colour changes are seen depending on the light and time.
The Taj Mahal looks pink in the morning, milky white in the evening, and golden in the moonlight. If you have visited the Taj Mahal more than once at different times, then you must have noticed that the colour of the Taj Mahal is different during the day and different at night.

name: Sajid Karke
review_text:
One of the best place that I have visit in life-time. Feels awesome to see it the naked eyes, all I saw it was on pictures, movies and videos but the reality is super awesome.
The Taj Mahal is located on the right bank of the Yamuna River in a vast Mughal garden. It was built by Shah Jahan in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal with the mosque, the guest house and the main gateway on the south, the outer courtyard and its cloisters were added subsequently. Ustad-Ahmad Lahori was the main architect of the Taj Mahal.The Taj Mahal is considered to be the greatest architectural achievement in the whole world!! Hospitality of people nearby was also excellent, so its good from the tourism perspective.

It is must visit place when someone is in Agra, Delhi or nearby cities.

name: Noel Alexander
review_text:
The best view is while viewing the Mausoleum from the entry gate.
Go as early as possible ~6AM to avoid the peak crowds and the heat during warmer seasons. Also, you should be able to see the first sunlight of the day falling on the mausoleum from the east.
Buy the entry tickets online it is more convenient and you may get a 5% discount.
Electric buggy service (Rs 20 per person)is available from the car parking to the main entrance and back.
Restroom facilities are well maintained.
They could make more areas of the mausoleum accessible and improve maintenance of the lawns and water fountains, etc.

name: Pettyfer410
review_text:
Last fall, I went there early in the morning on a tour with a certain company H. As you can see in the photos and videos, it is a very beautiful place, and even now, even after all this time, I am glad I visited.
We had planned to go in casual clothes, but the night before we ended up running a tour guide (there were no other tour participants other than ourselves, so it was essentially a private tour), so both my husband and I wore rented costumes. I regret it a lot. Women are allowed to wear sarees, but men are strongly advised not to wear costumes. 95% of tourists are in casual clothes, so its easy to see.
There was a baggage check immediately after entering the venue, so it was a good idea to keep the minimum amount of luggage.
You can get shoe covers and bottled water a little further away from the entrance.
It was a weekday according to the Japanese calendar, but it was before Duwali, and many people from India were there.
Since it was a tour, I drove there from Delhi. It took about 4 hours one way at high speed, but there were several service areas along the way, so I was able to travel without worrying too much about bathroom breaks.

name: Vinod Meena
review_text:
The Taj Mahal in Agra, India is a UNESCO World Heritage site that many consider a masterpiece of Indo-Islamic architecture and one of the worlds most admired monuments.
Some say its a symbol of the love between Shah Jahan and his wife, Mumtaz Mahal, and that its a reminder of the power of love.
Others say its one of the best examples of Mughal architecture, which blends Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles.
Here are some reviews from visitors:
Beauty: Some say the Taj Mahal is beautiful and evokes a depth of feeling. Others say its magnificent and serene.
Size: Some say the Taj Mahal is much bigger than they imagined.
History: Some recommend hiring a guide to learn about the history.
Architecture: Some say the Taj Mahals surface treatments are exquisite, and that its often described as a jewel box. Others say its characterized by a rhythmic combination of solids and voids, concave and convex shapes, light shadow, arches and domes, relief work in marble, and inlay work with precious and semi-precious stones.
Other attractions: Some mention the twin mosque buildings, lovely gardens, and museum that are part of the complex

name: kishore P
review_text:
The Taj Mahal, located in Agra, is truly awe-inspiring in its grandeur and beauty. The exquisite white marble structure, with intricate inlays and lush gardens, creates a serene and majestic ambiance. The symmetrical design and craftsmanship are breathtaking. The monuments romantic history and the mesmerizing reflection in the nearby water enhance its allure. Visiting the Taj Mahal is an unforgettable experience, offering a blend of history, art, and culture.
Thanks to AWIGN team.

name: Rajeevan Neeraj
review_text:
Went to Taj Mahal on a Monday. I got a government approved Photographer to do a mini photo shoot for me and my wife. His replies were prompt. He promised to edit all our videos that were taken on my phone but he did a crappy job. The songs were old and totally not in sync. The editing looked like it was done by a 12 year old. He told us he would edit about 20 photos for us. However he only edited 18 and editing looked like it was done on an app in an iPhone. We paid 6K INR for the service but the service output looked like only worth 1-2K INR.

Be wary of such people if you want to do a photoshoot.

His Instagram: tajmahal_photographyy

review_text:
Regardless of how famous he may be, he is truly impressive. Huge and well kept, authentic architecture, lush gardens and not too crowded. Furthermore, the accesses are located on semi-pedestrian avenues surrounded by greenery so as to detach themselves from the Indian chaos beforehand. Not very interactive as a monument, some QR codes for the various spots could be interesting.

review_translated_text: Aldila di quanto possa essere famoso e davvero impressionante. Enorme e ben tenuto, architettura autentica, giardini rigogliosi e non troppo affollato. Inoltre gli accessi sono situati su viali semipedonali immersi nel verde in modo da distaccarsi gia prima dal caos indiano. Poco interattivo come monumento, qualche qr code per i vari spot potrebbe essere interessante.

name: Umesh Ghimire
review_text:
Visiting one of the Seven Wonders of the World was an incredible experience! The Taj Mahal is truly a masterpiece of the Mughal era, and witnessing it in person was mesmerizing. The intricate design of the tomb, the historical significance, and the beautiful garden surrounding it all contribute to its grandeur. There are plenty of spots to sit and soak in the beauty of this iconic monument. However, be prepared for large crowds--this is the most crowded place Ive ever visited. The lines to enter can be quite long, so plan accordingly. Also, the entry fee for foreigners is 1000 rupees, which is something to keep in mind. Despite these challenges, the experience is well worth it!

name: Ameen Vayalil
review_text:
**Review of the Taj Mahal**

Visiting the Taj Mahal is an experience like no other. The moment you set eyes on the majestic white marble structure, it's easy to understand why it's one of the New Seven Wonders of the World. The intricate craftsmanship, symmetrical architecture, and the play of light on the marble at different times of the day are awe-inspiring. The monument, built by Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal, exudes a sense of love and reverence, making the atmosphere both romantic and serene.

The well-maintained gardens surrounding the Taj add to its beauty, offering peaceful spots for reflection and photography. Early morning visits are highly recommended, as the sunrise casts a golden hue over the monument, making it appear almost ethereal. The crowd is also thinner in the early hours, allowing for a more intimate experience.

One point to note is the high level of security and the prohibition of certain items, so it's essential to check the guidelines beforehand. The entry fee is higher for foreigners, but it's worth every penny for the chance to witness this UNESCO World Heritage site. The local guides are knowledgeable and provide deep insights into the history and symbolism of the Taj Mahal.

Overall, the Taj Mahal is not just a monument; it's a symbol of eternal love and a masterpiece of human artistry that should be on everyone's travel bucket list.

name: Sarath Babu Engoor
review_text:
Visiting the Taj Mahal is a breathtaking experience, but there are a few things to be aware of to ensure a smooth visit. The entry process has two main fees: 50 to enter the first gate and an additional 200 to go inside the Taj Mahal itself. Its essential to be cautious when dealing with guides. Many can be pushy, and some might try to overcharge or pressure you into additional services. If you plan on hiring a guide, make sure to confirm the price upfront and clarify what it includes. After your tour of the Taj Mahal, be sure to pay and settle the deal immediately.

Some guides might try to control your shopping experience by taking you to specific shops where they receive commissions, often leading you to a place falsely advertised as a mini Taj Mahal. These shops typically sell overpriced items. To avoid this, be firm in your choices and opt for exploring local markets on your own if possible.

The Taj Mahal is undoubtedly worth the visit, but a little caution can go a long way in ensuring a memorable experience.

name: Nilkamal Chetri
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is, without a doubt, one of the most breathtaking structures Ive ever seen. Its a testament to love, loss, and human ingenuity. Its ethereal beauty is almost overwhelming.
The pure white marble shimmers in the sunlight, and the intricate carvings are simply mesmerizing. The symmetry and proportion of the building are perfect, and the gardens that surround it create a serene oasis.
I visited during sunrise, and the soft pink hues that washed over the Taj were magical. Its an experience that will stay with me forever. However, I must admit that the crowds can be a bit overwhelming, especially inside the main mausoleum.
Despite the crowds, the Taj Mahal is a must-see for anyone visiting India. It's a place that truly takes your breath away.
Visited on
Weekday

name: Saurabh Gupta
review_text:
One needs to take an auto from agra railway station of fare 20 to Taj Mahal. Auto can even wait if you want to have food in between. Please be aware of auto who tell you to take Meena bazar, at my knowledge Meena bazar is no more and group of 3-4 shop fool you as Meena bazar.

There at Taj Mahal you need to take a ticket of 50 to visit the outer area and ticket 200 to visit inside Taj Mahal. Tickets are available in nearby shops and government ticket counters near Taj Mahal.

Please visit during early morning or in evening and carry an umbrella or cap if you are visiting during the afternoon in the summer season

During weekends/public holidays it will attract as many as 35K tourists making it too overcrowded to have personal space for photography...
Best time to visit is from October to March month...
Visit early morning, to avoid rush if you are visiting it on weekends/public holidays
On Friday Taj is closed for tourists.
Plan in advance or visit website: http://tajmahal.gov.in

name: Lazytadaki
review_text:
Stay overnight in Agra and visit the famous Taj Mahal, a tomb made entirely of marble.
It was apparently built by Shah Jahan, the fifth emperor of the Mughal Empire, for his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal, who died in 1631.

Unparalleled beauty, registered as a World Heritage Site
It is said that Shahjahan built it as a symbol of his eternal love for his beloved wife.
It is said that there are many wonderful stories.
White Marble (Marlboro) The beautiful appearance of the pure white marble reflecting the sunlight and changing its appearance during the day and night attracted many people, and it was a truly wonderful space that did not seem like a grave.
The delicate carvings and inlays on the marble are a masterpiece of Islamic art, and are truly magnificent.
All the buildings are symmetrical, demonstrating the architectural techniques of the time and the great power of the emperor.

Registered as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983.
It was a masterpiece of Indian architecture, a fusion of Mughal culture and Islamic art!

name: Azim Shabir Dar
review_text:
*Overview*

The Taj Mahal is a breathtakingly beautiful white marble mausoleum located in Agra, India. Its one of the most recognizable landmarks in the world and a testament to Indias rich history and architecture. Built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife, Mumtaz Mahal, the Taj Mahal is a stunning tribute to love and beauty.

*Architecture*

The Taj Mahals architecture is a blend of Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles, which was characteristic of the Mughal era. The monuments design is based on the principles of symmetry and geometry, with intricate marble inlays and ornate calligraphy adorning its walls. The central dome, surrounded by four smaller domes and four minarets, is a masterpiece of engineering and design.

*History*

The Taj Mahal was built between 1632 and 1653, taking over 22 years to complete. The story goes that Shah Jahan was so grief-stricken by Mumtaz Mahals death during childbirth that he decided to build a magnificent monument in her memory. The Taj Mahal was constructed using the finest materials and craftsmanship of the time, with thousands of workers laboring to create this wonder of the world.

*Features*

- The Taj Mahal changes color depending on the time of day and the lighting, appearing pinkish in the morning, white at noon, and golden at sunset.
- The intricate marble inlays depict floral patterns, passages from the Quran, and other ornate designs.
- The central chamber contains the tombs of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan, surrounded by ornate screens and marble work.
- The complex includes beautiful gardens, a mosque, and other auxiliary buildings.

*Tips and Insights*

- Best time to visit: Early morning or late evening to avoid the crowds and heat.
- Dress modestly and remove your shoes before entering the main mausoleum.
- Hire a guide to appreciate the history and significance of the Taj Mahal.
- Be prepared for security checks and crowds.

*Rating*

- Architecture: 5/5
- History: 5/5
- Beauty: 5/5
- Overall Experience: 5/5

The Taj Mahal is an awe-inspiring monument that exceeds expectations. Its stunning architecture, rich history, and romantic backstory make it a truly unforgettable experience. If you ever have the chance to visit, dont hesitate - its a wonder of the world that will leave you spellbound!

name: Rakesh Kumar
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is a majestic white marble mausoleum located in Agra, India. Here are the details, timing, and ways to reach:

*Details:*

- Location: Dharmapuri, Forest Colony, Tajganj, Agra, Uttar Pradesh 282001, India
- Built by: Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal

- Architecture: Mughal architecture, blending Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles
- Material: White Makrana marble

*Timing:*

- Opening hours: Sunrise to sunset (6:00 AM to 7:00 PM)
- Closed on: Fridays
- Best time to visit: Early morning or late evening to avoid crowds and heat

*Way to Reach:*

1. *By Air:* Nearest airport is Agra Airport (AGR), 7 km from the Taj Mahal. Delhi Airport (DEL) is 230 km away, with frequent flights and trains to Agra.
2. *By Train:* Agra Cantonment Railway Station (AGC) is the nearest, with trains from Delhi, Jaipur, and other cities.
3. *By Road:* Agra is connected to Delhi, Jaipur, and other cities via NH-2 and NH-3 highways. Buses and taxis are available.
4. *By Tour:* Book a guided tour or hire a taxi/auto-rickshaw from Agra city to reach the Taj Mahal.

*Additional Tips:*

- Buy tickets online or at the ticket counter
- Wear comfortable shoes and clothes
- Respect the monuments rules and regulations
- Hire a guide for a better understanding of the history and architecture
- Be prepared for security checks

*Ticket Prices:*

- Indians: 50 (daytime), 75 (sunrise/sunset)
- Foreigners: 1,100 (daytime), 1,300 (sunrise/sunset)

Note: Prices may vary, so check the official website or contact the Archaeological Survey of India for updates.

name: Topher Uy
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is indeed majestic and incredible, and all angles are Instagrammable. The only negative aspect I noticed when I was at the Taj Mahal was that I saw a guard beating a stray dog inside the palace. All the foreigners were shocked after witnessing that incident because the dog cried out in pain, and I saw his limbs swaying as if his bones were broken due to the severe beating by the guard or perhaps a police officer. As an animal lover, I was deeply shocked and disturbed by this incident, but unfortunately, there was nothing I or anyone else could do at that moment. I sincerely hope that animal lovers in India will take notice of this and work towards helping these poor dogs.

name: Ilo Kratins
review_text:
Youve gone to Agra to see the Taj Mahal, so go as early in the day as you can to avoid crowds, take your camera (no video equipment allowed, no tripods), leave all food and drink except clear water and anything else they might consider threatening to the monument behind. They give you a bottle of water and booties for entering the mausoleum when you pick up your tickets. Keep your eyeglasses and anything else loose and shiny secure by being aware of the monkeys, who will steal them right off your face, if they can, to get you to bribe them with fruit or juice to get them back (good luck). You can buy tickets at the entrance or online (online is easy, but dont mess up, as there are no refunds). If you goof up and dont get mausoleum tickets when you purchase your tickets online, you can buy the extra ticket there. A free electric shuttle will take high-value ticket purchasers (foreigners) through the combustion vehicle-free zone.

name: Rafa JB
review_text:
Definitely something not to miss if you travel to India. Doesnt disappoint. I recommend getting your tickets in advance online (you will avoid the queue to buy and you will arrive directly at the entrance queue, which at that time is short). The discount they give is better than the change. With these tickets they give you a discount of 50 rupees if you want to see the Red Fort later. Another option is to take them out in the morning and go just at dawn at 5:30, 5:45 or 6 and enter through the west door. Immediately go to the mosque area. From there, with the sun rising, the photos are spectacular. Next, go to the guest area (opposite side of the mosque) and with a mobile phone on the ground or spilling water on the ground you will get some impressive mirror photos. Then you can return to the central pond to take photos from the canal and finally from the cloisters. from the Darwan gate and at the entrance. The length of stay is 3 hours and be careful that they will constantly overwhelm you for guides, photos, etc. If it is not your plan, say no to everything. Transportation between the west gate and the entrance to the venue is free with admission. Otherwise its 20 rupees per person
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
Yes
review_translated_text: Sin duda algo para no perderse si viajas a la India. No defrauda. Recomiendo sacar las entradas con antelacion on line (evitareis cola para comprar y llegareis directos a la cola de entrada, que a esas horas es poca). El descuento que hacen es mejor que el cambio. Con esas entradas te hacen descuento de 50 rupias si quereis ver el Fuerte Rojo despues. Otra mas, sacarlas de manana e ir justo amaneciendo 5:30, 5:45 o 6 y entrar por la puerta oeste (West). Inmediatamente iros a la zona de la mezquita. Desde alli, con el sol saliendo, las fotos son espectaculares. Seguidamente id a la zona de huespedes (lado contrario a la mezquita) y con un movil en el suelo o derramando agua en el suelo saldran unas fotos especulares impresionantes, Luego podeis regresar al estanque central para hacer fotos desde el canal y finalmente desde los claustros de la puerta Darwan y en la entrada. El tiempo de estancia son 3 horas y cuidado que constantemente os van a agobiar para guias, fotos, etc. Si no es vuestro plan decir a todo que no. El transporte entre la puerta oeste y la entrada al recinto es gratis con la entrada. Sino son 20 rupias por persona

name: Ben
review_text:
Visiting TAJ MAHAL was an experience that transcended all my EXPECTATIONS.

This MAGNIFICENT MONUMENT, with its STUNNING ARCHITECTURE and PERFECT SYMMETRY, is a true TESTIMONY OF ETERNAL LOVE.

As I approached the entrance gates, I was immediately captivated by the IMMACULATE BEAUTY of the white marble that gleams in the sunlight.

Every INTRICATE DETAIL and every WELL MAINTAINED GARDEN around TAJ MAHAL contributes to an atmosphere of PEACE and TRANSIT.

Walking through the corridors and feeling the aura of devotion and respect is a PROFOUND experience.

The view of the YAMUNA RIVER in the background adds a touch of SERENITY to the already perfect setting.

Without a doubt, TAJ MAHAL is one of the WONDERS OF THE WORLD, and its BEAUTY and MEANING leave a lasting mark on the hearts of all who are lucky enough to visit it.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait
review_translated_text:
Visitar o TAJ MAHAL foi uma experiencia que transcendeu todas as minhas EXPECTATIVAS.


Este MONUMENTO MAGNIFICO, com sua ARQUITETURA DESLUMBRANTE e SIMETRIA PERFEITA, e um verdadeiro TESTEMUNHO DE AMOR eterno.


Ao me aproximar dos portoes de entrada, fui imediatamente cativado pela BELEZA IMACULADA do marmore branco que resplandece sob a luz do sol.


Cada DETALHE INTRICADO e cada JARDIM BEM CUIDADO ao redor do TAJ MAHAL contribuem para uma atmosfera de PAZ e TRANSITO.


Caminhar pelos corredores e sentir a aura de devocao e respeito e uma experiencia PROFUNDA.


A vista do RIO YAMUNA ao fundo adiciona um toque de SERENIDADE ao cenario ja perfeito.


Sem duvida, o TAJ MAHAL e uma das MARAVILHAS DO MUNDO, e sua BELEZA e SIGNIFICADO deixam uma marca duradoura no coracao de todos que tem a sorte de visita-lo.

name: suman lata
review_text:
Sundays at the Taj Mahal tend to be busier, especially during weekends. However, the crowd situation has improved recently, and it's not as crowded as it used to be. If you prefer a quieter experience, consider visiting between 9 am and 12 pm when it's less crowded.
I recommend buying tickets online in advance. This will save you time and ensure a smoother entry.
There are two value tickets for Indians: one for appreciating the view from the garden area (Rs 50) and another for exploring the tombs from upstairs and inside (Rs 250).
Additionally, there's a higher value ticket (Rs 1300) that allows you to avoid the crowd at the main entry.

name: Abhishek Singh
review_text:
I recently visited the Taj Mahal in Agra, and it was an incredible experience. The beauty of the Taj Mahal is truly unmatched, and I had a great time exploring its majestic architecture.

One of the highlights of my visit was the availability of a cameraman who can take stunning photos for you, making it easy to capture those perfect memories. I even shared some of my photos, and they turned out great! However, I found the ticket price to enter the mausoleum a bit expensive, so I wouldnt recommend going inside unless youre very keen on seeing the interiors.

For those worried about staying hydrated, theres good news! You can get Pune water inside the premises as long as you have a water bottle with you.

Overall, it was a memorable trip, and I enjoyed every moment of it. Just be mindful of the additional costs if youre planning to explore every aspect of the site.

name: Hari Krishnan
review_text:
Title: A Timeless Marvel - The Taj Mahal

Rating: 5/5

The Taj Mahal is an awe-inspiring wonder that transcends time and leaves an indelible mark on the heart. This majestic monument, nestled in the picturesque city of Agra, India, is a testament to love, beauty, and human ingenuity.

As I stepped into the complex, I was struck by the sheer scale and symmetry of the architecture. The marble exterior, adorned with intricate inlays of precious stones, glistened in the sunlight, radiating an ethereal glow. The reflecting pools and gardens added a sense of serenity, creating a perfect harmony of nature and art.

The history and romance surrounding the Taj Mahal are palpable. The story of Shah Jahans devotion to his beloved Mumtaz Mahal, and the monumental tribute he built in her memory, is a poignant reminder of the power of love.

The attention to detail and craftsmanship are astounding, with every aspect of the monument showcasing the skill and dedication of the artisans who built it. From the calligraphic inscriptions to the delicate floral patterns, every element is a masterpiece.

Visiting the Taj Mahal is an experience that will leave you spellbound and inspired. Its a reminder of the beauty and wonder that human creativity can achieve. Whether youre a history buff, an architecture enthusiast, or simply a romantic at heart, the Taj Mahal is an absolute must-see.

Tips:

- Plan your visit at sunrise or sunset to witness the Taj Mahal in all its glory.
- Hire a knowledgeable guide to uncover the rich history and secrets behind the monument.
- Respect the rules and regulations to preserve this incredible piece of history.

In conclusion, the Taj Mahal is an unforgettable experience that will etch itself in your memory forever. Its a celebration of love, beauty, and human achievement that will continue to inspire generations to come.

name: MUHAMMED SHAFI
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is a breathtaking marvel that lives up to its reputation as one of the worlds most beautiful buildings. This iconic ivory-white mausoleum on the banks of the Yamuna River in Agra is a must-visit destination for anyone traveling to India.

The intricate marble inlays, stunning symmetry, and majestic domes are awe-inspiring up close. The level of detail in the architecture and craftsmanship is truly remarkable, especially when you consider it was built in the 17th century.

The surrounding gardens and reflecting pools add to the serene atmosphere. Visiting at sunrise or sunset is particularly magical, as the changing light creates a mesmerizing effect on the marble.

While the site can get crowded, especially during peak tourist season, its well-managed with helpful staff and clear signage. Audio guides are available to learn about the history and symbolism behind this UNESCO World Heritage site.

Pro tips: Book tickets online in advance to avoid long queues, and consider hiring a knowledgeable local guide for deeper insights. Bring a good camera - youll want to capture every angle of this architectural gem.

Overall, the Taj Mahal is a bucket-list worthy experience that showcases the pinnacle of Mughal architecture and leaves visitors in awe of its timeless beauty and romantic legacy.

name: Sai Kumar
review_text:
How do you even put into words how incredible this monument is in real. No pictures do justice to it at all. A true wonder of the world. Hope the government invests some money to clean the marble facade like it did during the pandemic lockdown.

Some tips for the visit:

a. Indian or not, definitely take a guide, each and every story is worth listening to and you will find a guide at Rs. 400-500

b. For some reason they do not allow mobile phone chargers. They dont allow power banks too. Cell phones are allowed.

c. Buy a foot cover if you are planning to enter the mausoleum. Definitely suggest buying tickets online to avoid the queues.

d. Take your time and dont fall for hawkers around the monument. 99% of the stores around the monument are frauds, they sell fake marble, leather etc. If you need a souvenir, ask for the UP Govt Handloom and gift stores

name: Shaikh shaizan
review_text:
When it comes to the important and most iconic historical monuments in India, the Taj Mahal of Agra holds a special place. It is an architectural marvel located on the banks of the Yamuna River. The 42-acre Taj Mahal complex houses a mosque, a guest house, a gateway on the south, and a courtyard. Interestingly, the Taj Mahal is also a common topic for school competitions

About Taj Mahal
Travel Information
Day Tours
Views of Taj
Tourist Guide Map
UNESCO - World Heritage
Heritage Walks

Home Visiting Hours
Visiting Hours
Timing and Ticket Price to Visit the Taj Mahal in Agra, India

(Taj Mahal opens 30 Minutes before sunrise and closes 30 Minutes before sunset during normal operating days)

Taj Mahal is closed on Fridays for general viewing. Other days it is always open.

>
Ticket Outlets
(Buying Taj Mahal Ticket from Entry Gate Ticket Counter)

Taj Mahal Western Gate :- Tickets are available on Western Gate near Saheli Burj. (Timing-One Hour before Sunrise upto 45 Minutes before Sunset).

Taj Mahal Eastern Gate :- Tickets are available at Eastern Gate of Taj Mahal. (Timing-One Hour before Sunrise upto 45 Minutes before Sunset).

Taj Mahal Southern Gate :- No Entry from this gate at Present only Exit is allowed.
There are separate queues for Foreign tourists and Domestic tourists to enter to Taj and signs will direct you accordingly.

name: Lakshmi Prabha Srinivasan
review_text:
Asthetic pleasure - really stunned by seeing. The stories I heard passed through my mind and I was speechless when I visited for the first time.Every one needs to visit and experience it atleast once in their life time.

During my recent visit people are allowed to enter and exit from the western gate only.

If you book the entry ticket online, can avoid the big queue. You can enjoy the real charm if you visit early in the morning or just before sunset. During the day it will be sunny (carry sunglasses & hat) and crowded.

Rs.50 for visit the outer area for Indians and need take another ticket for Rs 200 to visit the thomb of Mumthaz. Book online for Rs250 which is the easiest option. Counter available inside too where we buy ticket to visit the thomb.

No eatables allowed inside except water. No selfie sticks allowed. Friday visitors are not allowed.

Hiring a professional guide and photographer is helpful. Drinking water is available inside. Cloak room service is good.

name: Anuroopa Gupta
review_text:
The Taj is magnificent! I loved how organized everything is now... compared to a decade back. The whole path is pedestrian, and you may hire golf carts approved by the government at 20 Rupees per person. Pre buying the tickets on the archeological site was great. There is option where you may choose a combo of all monuments you want to visit with defined time zones. The foreigner vs Indian prices vary widely but better do it online and get easy access and entry. Also photographers are available at the entry and you may bargain a good deal. I got one for 2000 Rupees for 50 pictures to be Transferred immediately to my phone no hard prints needed. We bought the sunset taj and mosoleum for day one. For day 2 we only bought the sunrise taj. We also had a guide pre hired. The sunrise was cloudy and rainy but got us empty spots.

Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
Yes

name: Abhishek Yadav
review_text:
What can I say, its the most amazing place I have ever visited. The story behind the Taj Mahal and the craftsmanship is incredible. I went as part of a tour, I would definitely recommend getting a tour guide as they can tell you all about the history.

We got there just before 8am and there were no wait times at all and this was a Saturday. There are photographers who will take your picture if you want them to but otherwise your tour guide will know all of the best spots to have them. I truly hope I get to visit again!

name: Rashmita Panigrahi
review_text:
The Taj Mahal, an iconic symbol of India, is located on the southern bank of the Yamuna River in Agra. Commissioned by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in 1632, the mausoleum was built in memory of his favorite wife, Mumtaz Mahal, who died during childbirth. This architectural masterpiece took over 20 years to complete, with contributions from thousands of artisans and craftsmen from across the empire and beyond, including Persia and Europe.

The Taj Mahal is renowned for its breathtaking symmetry, intricate marble inlays, and detailed carvings. The central dome, standing at 73 meters high, is surrounded by four smaller domes and four slender minarets at the corners. The marble walls are adorned with precious and semi-precious stones, forming elaborate floral patterns and calligraphy of Quranic verses. The complex also includes a mosque, a guest house, and expansive gardens with reflecting pools, enhancing the sites serene and majestic ambiance.

Recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983, the Taj Mahal is considered one of the finest examples of Mughal architecture and a symbol of Indias rich cultural heritage. It attracts millions of tourists annually, making it one of the most visited monuments in the world. The Taj Mahals beauty and historical significance continue to captivate people from all corners of the globe, serving as an enduring testament to love and artistic achievement.

General Entry ticket- Rs 50/-
Entry ticket to the Mosque - Rs 250/-
Guide fees- Rs. 500- 1000.(Depending upon time)

review_text: Taj Mahal is a great historical monument designed very beautifully. It is made up of white marbles which gives it a grand and bright look. It has attractive lawns, decorative trees, beautiful animals, etc in its surrounding areas. It is located in the Agra, UP at the bank of the Yamuna River. It is a very beautiful tomb made by the King Shah Jahan in the memory of Queen Mumtaz Mahal. In the ancient time Shah Jahan was a king and his wife was Mumtaz Mahal. Shah Jahan loved her wife a lot and he became very upset after her death. Then he decided to build a large grave in the memory of her wife. And he built Taj Mahal as a seventh wonders of the world.

name: Anand Nadkarni
review_text:
Very deservingly, it is one of the most magnificent architectural wonders in the world . Built with bricks and covered with marble with some beautiful in lay work with semi precious stone material. This form of art is still practised and the products are available in Agra. The symetery of the architecture and certain optical illusions are amazing. Taj appears different at dawn, dusk, in bright sunlight and on full moon nights, Definitely worth adding to the bucket list make sure you carry just your phone and wallet. Bags are not allowed, and you will need disposable shoe covers by the ticket, which includes the mausoleum . Just outside, there are a few souvenir shops . My advice would be by a thing if you feel it is worth it, and then don't compare prices.

Just all around a good experience given the circumstances. Would recommend this for everyone who visits taj for the first time and wants to make most of their visit.

name: sadarulla khan
review_text:
Place of love 
The Taj Mahal, located in Agra, India, is a stunning white marble mausoleum built between 1632 and 1653 by the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal. It is considered one of the greatest architectural achievements in Indo-Islamic architecture, blending Persian, Islamic, and Indian styles. The Taj Mahal is renowned for its intricate marble inlay work, expansive gardens, and symmetrical design. It is also a UNESCO World Heritage Site and attracts millions of visitors each year.........

Taj Mahal

Taj Mahal, Agra, India.



Agra, India: Taj Mahal

Taj Mahal, Agra, India, designated a World Heritage site in 1983.(more)

Taj Mahal, mausoleum complex in Agra, western Uttar Pradesh state, northern India. The Taj Mahal was built by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan (reigned 1628-58) to immortalize his wife Mumtaz Mahal ("Chosen One of the Palace"), who died in childbirth in 1631, having been the emperor's inseparable companion since their marriage in 1612. India's most famous and widely recognized building, it is situated in the eastern part of the city on the southern (right) bank of the Yamuna (Jumna) River. Agra Fort (Red Fort), also on the right bank of the Yamuna, is about 1 mile (1.6 km) west of the Taj Mahal.

name: C Bu
review_text:
Beautiful monument --

Agra's gastronomic offerings tantalize the taste buds with a unique blend of Mughlai and north india

The Taj Mahals Splendor
The Taj Mahal, located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India, is a true testament to architectural brilliance and everlasting love. This iconic monument was commissioned by Emperor Shah Jahan, who ruled the Mughal Empire from 1628 to 1658. He built the Taj Mahal as a mausoleum for his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal, who passed away in 1631.

The Taj Mahal's construction commenced in 1632 and was completed in 1653, taking approximately 21 years to build. It was constructed by a team of skilled artisans, architects, and craftsmen from various regions, including India, Persia (present-day Iran), and Central Asia.

The emperor's deep love for his wife, Mumtaz Mahal, was the driving force behind the construction of this magnificent monument. Mumtaz Mahal was Shah Jahan's favorite wife and his trusted companion. When she died while giving birth to their 14th child, Shah Jahan was devastated and resolved to create an unparalleled tribute to her memory.

The Taj Mahal stands as a symbol of eternal love and devotion. Its construction was a labor of love, with no expense spared. The emperor envisioned a structure that would surpass any other in beauty, grandeur, and magnificence. The Taj Mahal's design is a fusion of Islamic, Persian, and Indian architectural styles, resulting in a breathtaking masterpiece.

The Taj Mahal's pristine white marble facade, adorned with intricate floral motifs and calligraphy, is a sight to behold. The symmetry of the structure, the minarets, and the grand central dome all contribute to its visual splendor. The meticulous marble inlay work, known as pietra dura, showcases the remarkable craftsmanship of the artisans who worked on the monument.

Visiting the Taj Mahal is an experience that transports you to a bygone era. The historical significance and emotional resonance of this monument are palpable. It serves as a reminder of the enduring power of love and stands as a symbol of India's rich cultural heritage.

However, due to its popularity as a tourist attraction, the Taj Mahal can get crowded, especially during peak seasons. To fully immerse yourself in its beauty and appreciate its serenity, I recommend planning your visit during less busy periods or arriving early in the morning.

In conclusion, the Taj Mahal is an architectural masterpiece that reflects the depth of Emperor Shah Jahan's love for his wife, Mumtaz Mahal. Its timeless beauty, intricate craftsmanship, and historical significance make it a must-visit destination for anyone traveling to India. Prepare to be awe-struck by the Taj Mahal's magnificence and let its story of love and devotion leave an everlasting impression on your heart.

review_text: The Taj Mahal can be considered as the monument to the ultimate love and the highest achievement of the architect. The ebonies of the marble marble marble look crystalized in the light of the sun, and that marvel of human ingenuity and peaceful balance of form and design captivates the hearts of all who look or get inside at them. Taj Mahal is one of those lifetime experiences, whether each of the garden walls being a sculptural masterstroke, a poem. Be it the splendid visit of Taj Mahal, or strolling through its gardens or being mesmerized by its grand dome, you are quickly submerged in the powerful magnetos of the past and are competing to remember the unique, not leaving your mind the romantic love story is told over time. Were it not for a monument, it might have been a time-space continuum situation, a symbolic reminder of a marriage that alters in everyones lives who gazes. It is both a monument and a thorough walk through history, a worship of the unbent union that scares all those witnessing it for life.

name: Md. Atiq Ur Rahman
review_text:
The Taj Mahal (Hindi: ttaaj mhaal, Urdu: taaj mhl) is a royal mausoleum located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India. Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan built this magnificent monument in memory of his wife Arjumand Banu Begum popularly known as Mumtaz. The construction of the monument started in 1632 AD and was completed around 1653 AD.

The Taj Mahal (sometimes simply referred to as the Taj) is considered a striking example of Mughal architecture, combining Persian, Turkish, Indian and Islamic architecture. Although the white marble domed royal mausoleum is the most admired, the Taj Mahal is actually a complex monolithic structure as a whole. It was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983. Taj Mahal is one of the Seven Wonders of the World. It was then called a universally acclaimed masterpiece of world heritage.

Taj Mahal is one of the most beautiful monuments and fascinating landmarks in the world. An incredible memorial sculpture of love. A magnificent example of Islamic architecture that symbolizes peace and beauty. In 1631 AD, Shah Jahan, the most prosperous emperor of the Mughal period, was deeply saddened by the death of his second wife, Mumtaz.

Construction of the Taj Mahal began after Mumtazs death. The main mausoleum was completed in 1648 AD and the surrounding buildings and gardens were completed five years later. The Taj Mahal has attracted many tourists since its construction. Even the small town of Taj Ganji or Mumtazabad, on the south side of the Taj Mahal, was actually built to house tourists and markets to cater to the needs of tourists and artisans.

Currently, the Taj Mahal receives 2 to 3 million tourists, of which 200,000 are foreign tourists, making it one of the most popular tourist destinations in India. Most tourists come during the cold season in October, November and February. Air polluting vehicles are prohibited from approaching the Taj Mahal. Hence, tourists have to walk or take an electric bus to reach the Taj Mahal from the parking lot.

Currently, the cost of Taj Darshan is only 40 rupees for Indians. Taj entry fee for tourists from SAARC countries is Tk 530. And for the rest of the world it is 1000 rupees.

Archaeological Survey of India is also providing online tickets for tourists to visit the Taj Mahal from 25th December 2014.

Yes

taajmhl bishber apuurb sundr smRtisaudh o mnomugdhkr nidrshn /  bhaalobaasaar abishbaasy smrnniiy' bhaaskry /  islaamik sthaaptyer apuurb nidrshn yaa shaanti o saundryer prtiik /  1631 khrissttaabde shaahjaahaan, yini mughl aamler smRddhshaalii smraatt chilen, taaNr dbitiiy' strii mumtaaj er mRtyute prcnnddbhaabe shokaaht hy'e pdd'en / 


taajmhler nirmaann kaaj mumtaajer mRtyur pr shuru hy' /  muul smaadhitti smpuurnn hy' 1648 khristtaabde ebN er caardiker imaart ebN baagaan aaro paaNc bchr pre tairi hy' / nirmaanner pr thekei taajmhl bhu pryttkke aakrssit kreche /  emnki taajmhler dkssinn paashe chott shhr taaj gnyji baa mumtaajaabaad aasle gdd'e tolaa hy'echil pryttkder jny sraaikhaanaa o baajaar tairir uddeshye yaate pryttk ebN kaarigrder caahidaa puurnn hy' / 


brtmaane, taajmhle 2 theke 3 miliy'n pryttk aase yaar mdhye 2,00,000 pryttk bideshi, yaa eke bhaarter sbcey'e jnpriy' pryttnkendre prinnt kreche /  sbcey'e beshi pryttk aase tthaanddaa mausume akttobr, nbhembr o phebruy'aari maase /  baay'u duussnnkaarii yaanbaahn taajmhler kaache aasaa nissiddh /  taai, pryttkder gaadd'i raakhaar sthaan theke paay'e heNtte athbaa baidutik baase kre taajmhle aaste hy' /

name: Dr S K Maurya
review_text:
The Taj Mahal, located in Agra, India, is a world-renowned monument known for its stunning architecture and rich history. Built by the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal, the mausoleum is celebrated for its exquisite white marble structure and intricate inlay work. Visitors often describe the Taj Mahal as breathtaking and a symbol of eternal love.

Most reviews highlight the best time to visit the Taj Mahal as early in the morning at sunrise to avoid the large crowds and to experience the beautiful morning light reflecting off the marble. The period from October to March is ideal due to the pleasant weather, though it can get crowded during this peak season. Off-peak visits, particularly during the monsoon season (July to September), offer fewer crowds but come with the challenge of heavy rains.

Travelers are advised to book tickets in advance, especially for sunrise visits, to ensure a smooth experience. The monuments beauty is often described as awe-inspiring, with many visitors stating that photos do not do it justice. The surrounding gardens and the view of the Yamuna River add to the serene ambiance. However, the site can be overwhelmingly busy, and its recommended to visit with a knowledgeable guide to navigate the crowds and gain deeper insights into the history and architecture of the site.

Overall, the Taj Mahal is praised as a must-visit destination that lives up to its reputation as one of the worlds greatest wonders.

name: ROHIT YADAV
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is a major tourist attraction and attracts a large number of domestic and foreign visitors. About five million visitors visited Taj Mahal in the financial year 2022-23.A three-tier pricing system is in place, with a significantly lower entrance fee for Indian citizens and more expensive ones for foreigners. As of 2024, the fee for Indian citizens was 50, for citizens of SAARC and BIMSTEC countries, it was 540 and for other foreign tourists, it was 1,100. Visitors are allowed through three gates and as polluting vehicles are not allowed near the complex, tourists must either walk or take electric buses from the designated parking areas. The complex is open on all days except on Friday from one hour before sunrise to 45 minutes before sunset.The complex is open for limited night viewing on the day of the full moon, excluding the month of Ramadan.In 2019, to address overtourism, the site instituted fines for visitors who stayed longer than three hours.
The small town to the south of the Taj, known as Taj Ganji or Mumtazabad, was initially constructed with caravanserais, bazaars and markets to serve the needs of visitors and workers. Lists of recommended travel destinations often feature the Taj Mahal, which also appears in several listings of seven wonders of the modern world, including the New Seven Wonders of the World, a poll conducted in 2007. Foreign dignitaries often visit the Taj Mahal on trips to India.
The Taj Mahal was built on a small land plateau at the southern end of the circumscribed Agra city. Earlier, on this land there was a luxurious palace of Maharaja Jai   Singh of Jaipur under Rajputana state. Maharaja Shahjahan, in return, gave a large palace to Maharaja Jai   Singh of Jaipur in the middle of the city of Agra. An area of   about three acres was dug up, and by filling it with garbage, it was made fifty meters higher than the river level, so that there would be no dampness etc. Can be protected from. In the area of   the tomb, fifty wells were dug and filled with pebbles and stones to form a foundation. Then, instead of the traditional bamboo scaffolding, a huge brick structure, similar to a mausoleum, was built. This structure was so big that, according to the estimates of engineers, it would take years to remove it. The solution was that as per the orders of Shahjahan, the local farmers were given free rein to pick up as many bricks as they wanted in a day and the structure was cleaned overnight. To transport all the construction material and marble to the designated place, a fifteen kilometer long earthen slope was built. The stones were brought here by harnessing twenty to thirty oxen in specially made carts. A pulley system, consisting of an elaborate foot and beam, was created to move the pieces to their desired locations. The Rahat system was used to bring water from the river. Water from it was filled in a big tank built above. Then it was filled in three secondary tanks, from where it was transported to the places through tubes (pipes).

name: Shashwat Karna
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is truly a wonder of the world! This iconic monument is a breathtaking masterpiece, with its stunning white marble and intricate carvings. Visiting at sunrise offers a mesmerizing view as the monument glows with a soft, golden hue. The gardens are beautifully maintained, providing a serene atmosphere. Its an emotional and unforgettable experience, reflecting the timeless love story behind its creation. A must-see for anyone traveling to India!
Ive visited twice, and it never fails to impress. Hiring a guide is worth it to fully understand the history and details. The architecture is almost perfect, with a minor imperfection that adds character. The grounds are immaculate, and the whole place feels magical. If youre in India, the Taj Mahal is a must-visit.
Must visit in the early hours in winter.
The monument looks different at various times of the day, offering unique views. The reflection pool in front adds to its beauty, creating stunning mirror images. The interior is just as impressive with intricate marble inlay work. Be prepared for crowds, especially during peak tourist seasons. Despite this, the experience remains peaceful and awe-inspiring. The nearby Yamuna River adds to the scenic beauty of the location. You can also explore the smaller, charming buildings surrounding the Taj. Don't forget to wear comfortable shoes, as theres a lot of walking involved. Visiting the Taj Mahal is not just about seeing a building; its about experiencing a piece of history and a symbol of enduring love. The local markets outside are great for picking up souvenirs to remember your visit.

name: Nikhil Arora
review_text:
Beauty at its best, Always go in pleasant weather, no need for doing guard here, if you are from north india.

Get photographs clicked they charge 300 for 10 photos and transfer them to your mobile. Or 700 for 10 photos hard copies.

Ticket is 50 and 200 more if you want to go upside and inside.

No eatables are allowed inside, no kids toys are allowed, locker facility is available. Car parking is available. 20 rs charge for shoe cover, drinking water is available freely inside. Check online for facts and unique things about taj and feel yourself. It takes 2 hours at max for complete taj visit. Prefer going in the morning at 6 or at pleasant weather.
There is metro station just outside.

name: Angus
review_text:
Absolutely beautiful. We arrived just before sunrise, spent 3 hours there (max. time allowed per ticket) and of course it was a highlight of our trip.

No queues at 5 am (on a weekday) to buy the tickets or entry. Staff were wide awake and helpful. A free bottle of water and shoe covers are given free.

You will be approached by guides and professional photographers, a polite refusal is fine.

Carry as little as possible in your bag to get through security smoothly.

Watch out for the monkeys in the outer compound.

Once inside the main area, amateur photographers will try to guide you to the best photo spots and take pictures for you with your phone.

We had a little old man do it for us (free at first, he never asked for money) at first we reluctantly accepted his help, and were SO glad we did. He knew all the best spots and angles. He took awesome pics and short videos so at the end we tipped him gladly.

Inside the mausoleum was worth the extra admission. The attendants inside will suck you in with rapid fire information, then ask for a tip.

There is a museum to the left of the main area but it only opens at 9am.

It was an effort to get up so early but well worth it to avoid the crowds and see the magnificent Taj Mahal in the early morning light.

Pity about the fountains and ponds being empty. Some renovation and getting them working would have made the main area even more magical and created a nice cooling effect.

But this was a small thing. We were so glad we came.

name: giriraj bajaj
review_text:
The Taj Mahal: A Monument Steeped in Pristine Beauty

The Taj Mahal isnt just a landmark, its an embodiment of love and architectural mastery. Heres what awaits you:

Unparalleled Beauty: The ivory-white marble gleams under the sun, reflecting a luminescence that takes your breath away. The intricate carvings, the delicate inlay work, the perfect symmetry - every detail conspires to create a masterpiece of Mughal art.

Impeccable Upkeep: The surrounding gardens are a marvel of landscaping. Lush green walkways, reflecting pools, and meticulously manicured hedges frame the Taj Mahal, creating a sense of serenity and enhancing its grandeur. The cleanliness adds to the reverence you feel while exploring the complex.

Effortless Management: The authorities have done a commendable job managing the crowds. Clear pathways, designated photography areas, and helpful staff ensure a smooth and enjoyable visit.

Photographers Paradise: Speaking of photography, the Taj Mahal offers a plethora of stunning backdrops. Capture the iconic central dome reflected in the still waters of the reflecting pool, or frame the monument through the grand archway. Whether youre a professional or an amateur, the Taj Mahal will leave you with unforgettable pictures.

A Must-Visit: The Taj Mahal is more than a monument; its a poem etched in marble. The experience is truly magical, leaving an indelible imprint on your memory. Dont miss the chance to witness this architectural marvel in person.

name: KUMAR ASHUTOSH
review_text:
Hi All,
Taj Mahal is a renowned place and also under 7 wonders of the world, it was well organised pls book your ticket for entry online, it is easily available. Place was good enough, timing is strict from morning 11 to 5 in evening so plan your trip accordingly. You may face photographers approaching for photos, negotiate as per your convenience. We have clicked from our own phone and it was good enough. If you want to visit inside taj Mahal there is another ticket of aroung 350 per person I dont find it worth it. Overall one time go, very exhausting due to heat so take water along with you.

name: Anastasiya Episheva
review_text:
ALL WHAT YOU NEED TO KNOW BEFORE GOING THERE

#buy ticket online (full one so no need to be in line)
#rent a saree (7 min away from taj they have a shop for it 1000/2000)
#best time to go evening around 4pm
#museum working only 9-5pm
#you can get your shoes cover near taj main building
#plenty of drinking water spots
#toilets are in the end near the gate
#do your pics first and then go explore
#opening time 5am (!) be there early!!! Closing time 7.30pm
#you have only 3 hours to explore or you will pay extra fee
#it's not allowed to take videos on camera after arch
#no sticks, no suggests etc
#inside there are a lot of photographers you can buy pics from them, try it, they are really cool and know the spots

Life hacks:
# in the morning go at 5am with online ticket (just entrance) and take pics
#in the morning park is empty especially if you go close to white building and walk around, they have the best spots there for pics from the sides (no need a ticket)
#in the being go around 4pm and you can explore museum and main building, also have your pics with a best light (you will need a full ticket)
#pay for the guys and got your shots and videos quickly (1000-1500)
#morning time you can go for free to the river side it's the same view from there
#sunset time you can go also to the park in the cross river side (!) 300 and enjoy the view

name: Abinash
review_text:
The Taj Mahal is a breathtakingly beautiful monument to love and devotion. The intricate marble work, the perfectly symmetrical design, and the serene gardens all come together to create an unforgettable experience. The changing colors of the marble as the sun rises and sets are a sight to behold. The history and romance surrounding the Taj Mahal only add to its allure. Its a must-visit destination for anyone interested in architecture, history, or simply experiencing one of the most stunning wonders of the world. The Taj Mahal is a true masterpiece that will leave you in awe.

name: Elis Nayara Prado de Godoi
review_text:
The expectations were higher, of course, its a beautiful, imposing building, it doesnt need any comments, but the number of scammers around and relentlessly approaching you almost ruins your experience here.

If you buy tickets at the entrance, there is a small window where you will get free bottled water and shoe covers (so no need to buy from people offering them on the street if you dont want to). You can buy your tickets alone at the entrance, no matter what the people who approach you on the street tell you.

At the entrance, people say they work there and tried to offer free tours, free photos... all scams, of course, so always be careful and refuse anything you dont want to pay for.

There are water fountains inside TAJ, but there are no vendors and you cannot bring food.

Dont take a tripod, drone, cigarette, pen... the list of what you cant enter is huge.

At 2pm, TAJ wasnt that crowded, we were able to take beautiful photos, but when we were leaving at 5pm, the number of people had tripled. It was 35 degrees on the day and there are few shadows.

Inside TAJ you can take photos wherever you want, but some photographers try to convince you otherwise, dominating the best photo spots, as if you could only take photos there if you paid them. Dont accept this, organize your space and only leave after photographing as you wish.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
Not sure
review_translated_text:
A expectativa era maior, claro, e uma linda construcao, imponente, dispensa comentarios, mas a quantidade de golpistas ao redor e te abordando incansavelmente quase estraga sua experiencia aqui.


Se voce comprar os ingressos na entrada, ha uma pequena janela onde voce pegara garrafa de agua gratuita e protetores para os sapatos (portanto nao precisa comprar das pessoas que oferecem na rua se voce nao quiser). Voce pode comprar seus ingressos sozinho na entrada, nao importa o que as pessoas que te abordam na rua te digam.


Na entrada, pessoas dizem que trabalham la e tentaram oferecer tour gratuito, foto gratuito.. tudo golpe, claro, entao esteja sempre atento e recuse tudo que nao quiser pagar.


Ha bebedouros de agua dentro do TAJ, mas nao ha vendedores e voce nao pode levar comida.


Nao leve tripe, drone, cigarro, caneta.. a lista do que nao pode ingressar e enorme.


As 2 da tarde, o TAJ nao estava tao cheio, pudemos tirar lindas fotos, mas quando estavamos saindo as 5 da tarde, o numero de pessoas tinha triplicado. Fazia 35 graus no dia e ha poucas sombras.


Dentro do TAJ voce pode tirar foto onde voce quiser, mas alguns fotografos tentam te convencer do contrario, dominando os melhores pontos para foto, como se voce so pudesse tirar foto la se pagasse a eles. Nao aceite isso, arrume seu espaco e so saia depois de fotografar como quiser.

name: ABHISHEK KAPOOR
review_text:
The Taj Mahal isnt just a monument; its a poem etched in marble, a love story whispered across centuries. Visiting this UNESCO World Heritage Site is an experience unlike any other. As you approach the white marble facade, its delicate beauty takes your breath away. The sheer scale and intricate details leave you speechless.

Built by Mughal emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his third wife Mumtaz Mahal, the Taj Mahal is more than just a tomb. Its a testament to enduring love, a masterpiece of Mughal architecture, and a symbol of India itself.

Be prepared for crowds, especially during peak season. Purchase your tickets online in advance to avoid long queues. Also, photography inside the main mausoleum is not permitted.

name: SUNIL GUJJAR
review_text:
The Taj Mahal lit. Crown of the Palace) is an ivory-white marble mausoleum on the right bank of the river Yamuna in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India. It was commissioned in 1631 by the fifth Mughal emperor, Shah Jahan (r. 1628-1658) to house the tomb of his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal; it also houses the tomb of Shah Jahan himself. The tomb is the centrepiece of a 17-hectare (42-acre) complex, which includes a mosque and a guest house, and is set in formal gardens bounded on three sides by a crenellated wall.

Construction of the mausoleum was completed in 1648, but work continued on other phases of the project for another five years. The first ceremony held at the mausoleum was an observance by Shah Jahan, on 6 February 1643, of the 12th anniversary of the death of Mumtaz Mahal. The Taj Mahal complex is believed to have been completed in its entirety in 1653 at a cost estimated at the time to be around 5 million, which in 2023 would be approximately 35 billion (US$77.8 million).

The building complex incorporates the design traditions of Indo-Islamic and Mughal architecture. It employs symmetrical constructions with the usage of various shapes and symbols. While the mausoleum is constructed of white marble inlaid with semi-precious stones, red sandstone was used for other buildings in the complex similar to the Mughal era buildings of the time. The construction project employed more than 20,000 workers and artisans under the guidance of a board of architects led by Ustad Ahmad Lahori, the emperors court architect.

name: VELRAJ T
review_text:
Marvellous..

Must visit atleast once in a life time.

Dont take guide.. if u want take then for 300 to 400.. also Avoid professional photographers unless u wanted a printed photo.. i paid about a lot(only for soft copies) and then came to know that they cheated me.. they didnt accept for less than 10 photos. And they charge 40 rs for each photo.. seems 20 rs is reasonable for soft copy as they are taking more photos.. my phone camera quality was actually good... I should have considered photographers when i exit the taj mahal.. they were very rude also...

There s a museum inside the campus.. you can find very interesting things used by moghuls.. i liked the plate that turns color or breaking into pieces when it is exposed with poisonous food.

Car parking 100 rs.. take 20 rs battery operated car for 1km ride to reach the main gate.. get tickets online if possible..

There is a clock room to keep things.. food items are not.allowed.. selfie sticks are also not allowed..

Purchase shoe cover for 10 rs for mausoleum visiting.. photography is prohibited inside mausoleum..

review_text:
The five star rating is strictly for Taj Mahal, it is indeed a beautiful sight to see and pictures of Taj Mahal don't do justice to how great it looks in person. That being said, advice to visitors - DO NOT get tour guides, I got one and all they do is blabber random facts all the time and kind of ruins the peacefulness of the place and waste your time. My guide would not shut up and let me go near the Taj Mahal, and on top of that they push you to buy random things from vendors. These guides are suppose to be authorized, but please don't get it. I suggest googling facts about Taj Mahal before going there and then just enjoy the place by yourself, take in the beauty of the Taj Mahal.

name: Defen Chen
review_text:
Avoid for the so called "free tour guide for foreigners", it's scam.

The guide will take you to the marble shop and gem shop to scam you, please avoid.

The building and the story behind it are world class, but please be careful of scammers, there is no free tour here, if anyone tells you that there is a free tour for foreigners please avoid it, this is a scam.

After the tour, he will take you to the shop of the so-called family responsible for repairing Taj Mahal marble and force you to buy marble, but this family does not exist at all.

name: Jesus
review_text:
One of the 7 wonders of the world  well deserves 5 stars!  It all depends on the expectations you have about things, but I was very impressed by this marble mausoleum with a lot of meticulously cared for details. I visited it at dawn and the feeling was incredible! The sun was caressing the marble and the light projected was perfect! I bought the ticket at the time without any problem and thats it! Keep in mind that there are a lot of things that you cannot bring inside the venue, such as a selfie stick , pens, notebooks, books... The experience was incredible! 
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
No
review_translated_text: Una de las 7 maravillas del mundo  bien merece 5 estrellas!  Todo depende de las expectativas que tengas en las cosas pero a mi me impresiono mucho este mausoleo de marmol con un monton de detalles minuciosamente cuidados. Lo visite al amanecer y la sensacion fue increible! El sol iba acariciando el marmol y la luz proyectada era perfecta! La entrada la compre en el momento sin ningun problema y eso si! Ten en cuenta que hay un monton de cosas que no puedes llevar dentro del recinto, como palo selfie , boligrafos, libretas, libros... La experiencia fue increible!

The Taj Mahal is truly a wonder of the world! This iconic monument is a breathtaking masterpiece of Mughal architecture, with its stunning white marble and intricate carvings. Visiting at sunrise offers a mesmerizing view as the monument glows with a soft, golden hue. The gardens are beautifully maintained, providing a serene atmosphere. Its an emotional and unforgettable experience, reflecting the timeless love story behind its creation. A must-see for anyone traveling to India!
